{META_DATA}: 12 YEARS A SLAVE
{META_DATA}: Written by
{META_DATA}: John Ridley
{META_DATA}: CARD: 1841
{META_DATA}: FADE IN:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 1 INT. TOWNHOUSE/STUDY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -EARLY APRIL, 1841- We are close on a PAIR OF BLACK HANDS as they open A
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FINELY WRAPPED PACKET OF VIOLIN STRINGS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WE CUT TO the hands stringing a VIOLIN.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's not a high end piece, but it is quite nice.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WE CUT TO a wide shot of the study.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sitting in a chair with violin in hand is SOLOMON NORTHUP; a man in his late twenties.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Everything about Solomon, his mien and manner, is distinguished.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But he, too, seems a hardy individual.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Someone who has known manual labor in his time.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon begins to lightly play his violin, as if testing the strings, their tuning.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Satisfied, Solomon begins to play vigorously.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he does, we make a HARD CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. HOUSE/LIVING ROOM - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We come in on a lively affair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A dinner party is being thrown within the confines of a fairly stately house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In attendance are EIGHT COUPLES.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All are WHITE and all are FAIRLY YOUNG, in their early twenties.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The men and women are dressed in very fine attire.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We should get the sense that for the most part they are people of means.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The furniture has been set aside in the living room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At the moment the couples are engaged in the dancing of a REEL.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The music they are dancing to is being played by Solomon, having cut directly from the tune he was previously playing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He plays with a light determination, and in no way seems possessed with empty servitude.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon concludes the reel, and the dancers break into enthusiastic applause, which is followed by personal thanks and congratulations from all.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It should be clear that despite their respective races there is much admiration and appreciation for Solomon's abilities.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. NORTHUP HOUSE/BEDROOM - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is a Saturday morning.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clad in her finest attire is ANNE; Solomon's wife, a few years younger than he.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see also the Northup children: MARGARET who is eight, and ALONZO who is five.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are handsome, and well groomed kids.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anne straightens up the children.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She finishes,
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 2.
{META_DATA}: 3 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: she rises up and stands behind them, almost as if preparing to pose for a portrait.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They all wait a moment, then Solomon enters the foyer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stands and looks admiringly at his family.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ADMIRINGLY stressed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It isn't that he doesn't have love for them, he does as well.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But in the moment, he truly admires his greatest accomplishment: a family that is healthy and well and provided for.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He goes to his children, and hands each a coin, then goes to Anne.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gives her a kiss on the cheek.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The children giggle at the sight.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. STREET - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon and his family are out walking along the streets and groves of Saratoga.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The streets are well populated this morning with many people out strolling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Most are WHITE, but there are BLACKS as well.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are FREED BLACKS who mingle fairly easily - though not always completely - with the whites.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see, too, a few BLACK SLAVES who travel with their WHITE MASTERS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: These pairings are largely from the south and - despite the fact the blacks are slaves - they are not physically downtrodden, not field hands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are well dressed and "leading apparently an easy life" - comparatively speaking - as they trail their masters.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they walk, Solomon and his family arrive to an intersection well-worn and muddied from horse and cart traffic.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon and his children easily jump across the muck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anne stands at the lip of the puddle, calls for Solomon to help her across.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANNE
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon... Solomon, turning back to his wife with a broad smile waving her forward:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Come, Anne.
{DIALOGUE}: Jump.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The children, now smiling as well, egg their mother on.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ALONZO MARGARET
{DIALOGUE}: Jump.
{DIALOGUE}: You can make it.
{DIALOGUE}: I've done it.
{DIALOGUE}: You can make it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANNE
{DIALOGUE}: I will not ruin my dress.
{DIALOGUE}: Catch me!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon moves close, holds out his arms.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Yet, there's still just a bit of mischievousness in his eyes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anne gives her husband a lightly stern look to which Solomon replies.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 3.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I will catch you, Anne.
{META_DATA}: (BEAT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: I will.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Again, lightly stern:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANNE
{DIALOGUE}: You will.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And with that Anne takes the leap.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon catches her, swings her around grandly and sets her down lightly to the delighted applause of the children.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: That done, Solomon takes Anne's hand and leads her on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Solomon and his family make their way, among the slaves on the street, we see one in particular; JASPER.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he trails his MASTER he can't help but note Solomon and his family as they enter A STORE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His intrigue of this most handsome and harmonious group should be obvious.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With his Master occupied, Jasper moves slyly toward the STORE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Frozen on the spot, Jasper looks on admiringly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly a voice barks out-
{CHARACTER_NAME}: A VOICE (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: Jasper!
{DIALOGUE}: Come on!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. STORE - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We are inside the store of MR. CEPHAS PARKER; a white man and a supplier of general goods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon greets him
{META_DATA}: WITH:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Parker.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PARKER
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Northup.
{DIALOGUE}: Mrs. Northup.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With money in hand the Northup children move quickly about the store looking for items to purchase.
{META_DATA}: CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anne looks over some silks and fabrics.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Parker suggests
{META_DATA}: TO SOLOMON:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PARKER (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: A new cravat, Solomon?
{DIALOGUE}: Pure silk by way of the French.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: We are in need of a fresh carry all for the Mrs's travels.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PARKER
{DIALOGUE}: A year's passed?
{DIALOGUE}: Off to Sandy Hill?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANNE
{DIALOGUE}: I am.
{DIALOGUE}: Using a long pole, Mr. Parker fetches down a CARRY ALL from an upper shelf.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PARKER
{DIALOGUE}: Something to suit your style, but sturdy enough for the forty miles round trip.
{DIALOGUE}: Handing the Bag to Anne, she is immediately taken by it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANNE
{DIALOGUE}: It's beautiful.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{META_DATA}: (CAUTIOUSLY)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At what price?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANNE
{DIALOGUE}: We will take it.
{DIALOGUE}: Children, come see what your father has just purchased for me.
{DIALOGUE}: As the children run over - chattering excitedly about the new gift - they RUN PAST JASPER who has quietly entered the store.
{DIALOGUE}: At the checkout counter sits a portrait of WILLIAM HENRY HARRISON, the edges draped in black crepe.
{DIALOGUE}: Before the book sits a LEDGER.
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Parker asks of Solomon:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PARKER
{DIALOGUE}: If you would sign our condolence book.
{DIALOGUE}: My hope is to find a way to forward it to the Widow Harrison.
{DIALOGUE}: Sad days for the nation.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, certainly.
{DIALOGUE}: Poor Mrs. Harris and her children.
{DIALOGUE}: I hope brighter times ahead.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 4A.
{META_DATA}: 5 CONTINUED: (2)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jasper looks scared, timid.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's as though he'd like to engage, but is unsure of as to how.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Noting Jasper, Parker
{META_DATA}: SAYS:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PARKER
{DIALOGUE}: A moment, sir, and you will be assisted.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: If we could discuss the price...
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 5.
{META_DATA}: 5 CONTINUED: (3)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PARKER
{DIALOGUE}: Forgive me, Mrs. Northup.
{DIALOGUE}: A customer waits.
{DIALOGUE}: Welcome, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: To Jasper, with good nature:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Shop well, but mind your wallet.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PARKER
{DIALOGUE}: Ignore the gentleman's nonsense.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, may I interest you in a new cravat?
{DIALOGUE}: Pure silk by way of the-- Before Parker can finish, the door opens.
{DIALOGUE}: It's Jasper's Master, FITZGERALD.
{DIALOGUE}: He's stern, clearly displeased.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FITZGERALD
{DIALOGUE}: Jasper!
{META_DATA}: (TO PARKER)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: My regrets for the intrusion.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: No intrusion.
{DIALOGUE}: Fitzgerald looks to Solomon.
{DIALOGUE}: It is a cold glare as though he wasn't speaking to, and has no interest in a response from a black man.
{DIALOGUE}: Looking back to Parker:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FITZGERALD
{DIALOGUE}: Good day, sir.
{META_DATA}: 6
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. NORTHUP HOUSE/DINING ROOM - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anne, busy in the kitchen, puts the final touches to the meal, which is just about to begin.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon, in the meanwhile, sits at the head of the table reading from a NEWSPAPER.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He reads to his children solemn news of the funeral arrangements for the recently deceased President Harrison.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: "Thus has passed away from earth our late President."
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon starts from the top of the article.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: "During the morning, from sunrise, the heavy bells had been pealing forth their slow and solemn toll while the minute guns announced that soon the grave would receive its trust.
{DIALOGUE}: Our city as well as our entire nation has been called to weep over the fall of a great and good man.
{DIALOGUE}: One who was by the wishes of a large majority of our
{META_DATA}: (MORE) (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 5A.
{META_DATA}: 6 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: people raised to fill the highest place of trust within their gift.
{DIALOGUE}: William Henry Harrison."
{DIALOGUE}: A long moment of quiet, the family continuing to eat.
{DIALOGUE}: Then, from Margaret:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARGARET
{DIALOGUE}: Will you read it again?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANNE
{DIALOGUE}: Not just now, darling.
{DIALOGUE}: Anne enters the dining room and places a large chicken at the center of the table.
{DIALOGUE}: As she takes a seat, all heads are bowed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARGARET
{DIALOGUE}: For food that stays our hunger, For rest that brings us ease, For homes where memories linger, We give our thanks for these.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ALL
{DIALOGUE}: Amen.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Margaret, that was wonderful.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARGARET
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you, Papa.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Alonzo, do you have something to say?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ALONZO
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, I helped Momma make this.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANNE
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, and you were such a good help.
{DIALOGUE}: Especially making the gravy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARGARET
{DIALOGUE}: Papa, I would very much like to learn how to play the violin.
{DIALOGUE}: Could you teach me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ALONZO
{DIALOGUE}: Me too!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARGARET
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, but I asked Papa first.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Both of you, calm down.
{DIALOGUE}: We will have our first lesson after this wonderful dinner.
{DIALOGUE}: And on that note, let's start eating.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 5B.
{META_DATA}: 6 CONTINUED: (2)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The family all tuck in to their meal.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The scene is one of warmth and happiness.
{META_DATA}: 6.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 7 INT. NORTHUP HOUSE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon and Anne have fun and difficulty putting the unruly children to bed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are tucked in, and each given a kiss good night.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Margaret lays down to sleep, Anne blows out the candle darkening the room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Silhouetted in the doorway, Solomon takes Anne in his arms, holds her tightly as they both luxuriate in the simple, beautiful gift that is their children.
{META_DATA}: 7A
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. NORTHUP HOUSE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Now alone together, we see Anne and Solomon wrapped in each other's arms.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Beyond being physically close, emotionally close, they are just so very comfortable with one another.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are the very representation of a couple who are made for each other.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They look at each other for a prolonged time.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{META_DATA}: (COMICALLY FORLORN)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Three weeks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two days.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANNE
{DIALOGUE}: It is the custom.
{DIALOGUE}: I wonder what you'll do without me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I won't stay idle.
{DIALOGUE}: SOLOMON's eyes lower.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANNE
{DIALOGUE}: Darling, it's good money.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: If only I didn't have to share your cooking with other people.
{DIALOGUE}: ANNE holds his gaze.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANNE
{DIALOGUE}: You don't.
{DIALOGUE}: They kiss.
{META_DATA}: 8 OMIT
{META_DATA}: 7.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 9 EXT. NORTHUP HOUSE - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We are just outside the Northup house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A CARRIAGE waits with a DRIVER.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anne and the children are dressed for travel - Anne sporting HER NEW CARRY ALL.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Driver loads bags into the carriage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For her parting gift, Anne gives her husband a kiss.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Travel safely.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANNE
{DIALOGUE}: Stay safely.
{DIALOGUE}: Anne and the children loaded up, the Driver chides the horse and the carriage heads off.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon waves a hearty good bye to his wife and children.
{META_DATA}: 10
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. PARK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon is now out for a stroll.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He passes two men - two in particular - who stand outside conversing with MR. MOON himself: MERRILL BROWN and ABRAM HAMILTON.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brown is about 40, with a countenance indicating shrewdness and intelligence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hamilton is closer to 25, a man of fair complexion and light eyes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Both are finely, if perhaps a bit garishly, dressed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hamilton, as Solomon describes him, slightly effeminate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Moon, spotting Solomon:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MR. MOON Call the Devil's name... There he is now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mr. Northup...!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: I have two gentlemen who should make your acquaintance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Messrs. Brown and Hamilton.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: Sir.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MR. MOON Mr. Northup, these two gentlemen were inquiring about distinguished individuals, and I was just this very moment telling them that Solomon Northup is an expert player on the violin.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: He was indeed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Moon is being overly gracious.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 8.
{META_DATA}: 10 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: Taking into consideration his graciousness and your modesty, may we trouble you for a moment of your time to converse, sir?
{META_DATA}: 11
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. PARK/PAVILION - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We make a jump to a green space.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon, Brown and Hamilton are sitting at a bench.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: A circus?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: That is our usual employee.
{DIALOGUE}: The company currently in the city of Washington.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: Circus too constricting a word to describe the talented and merry band with which we travel.
{DIALOGUE}: It is a spectacle unlike most have ever witnessed.
{DIALOGUE}: Creatures from the darkest Africa as yet unseen by civilized man.
{DIALOGUE}: Acrobats from the Orient able to contort themselves in the most confounding manners.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: And I myself in aide of Mr. Brown; an internationally renowned practitioner in the art of prestidigitation.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: We are on our way thither to rejoin the company having left for a short time to make a small profit from our own exhibitions.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: The reason for our inquiry with Mr. Moon...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: We had just a devil of a time in procuring music for our
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 9.
{META_DATA}: 11 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: entertainments.
{DIALOGUE}: Men of true talent seemingly in short supply.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you sir...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: If we could persuade you to accompany us as far as New York... We would give you one dollar for each day's service and three dollars for every night played at our performances.
{DIALOGUE}: In addition we would provide sufficient pay for the expenses of your return from New York here to Saratoga.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: You understand this is all very sudden.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: Consider it an opportunity to see
{META_DATA}: THE COUNTRY--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: It's intriguing...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: If there is any way in which you would give consideration to the offer... Solomon gives the whole deal one last consideration.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: The payment offered is enticement enough, as is my desire to visit the metropolis.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: We are delighted, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: So delighted.
{DIALOGUE}: Though we would add that our travel plans--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: We would like to depart with haste.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 10.
{META_DATA}: 11 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: As luck would have it, my wife and children are traveling.
{DIALOGUE}: I will write her of our plans.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: Excellent!
{DIALOGUE}: I would beg you collect yourself, then we may proceed.
{META_DATA}: 12
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. NORTHUP HOUSE/BEDROOM - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Back in his house, we see Solomon packing: putting some clothes in a travel case, and collecting his violin as well.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 13 INT. NORTHUP HOUSE/STUDY - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon sits down to write a letter; pen poised over paper with already a few lines written.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But Solomon thinks better of it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WITH LITTLE THOUGHT HE TEARS THE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PAPER AND SETS IT ASIDE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WE SHOULD GET THE SENSE THAT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE ABSOLUTE VALUE OF BEING ABLE TO COMMUNICATE BY LETTER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: IS LOST ON SOLOMON.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THIS FACT WILL HAVE GREAT WEIGHT IN
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE NEAR FUTURE.
{META_DATA}: 14
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SOLOMON'S HOUSE/INT. COVERED CARRIAGE - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon enters the buggy, carpet bag in hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brown and Hamilton are waiting.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They ride in a covered carriage led by a pair of "noble" horses.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: No letter to post?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: No need.
{DIALOGUE}: My return will coincide with my family's.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: We're off then.
{META_DATA}: 15
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. PUB - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -MID TO LATE APRIL, 1841- We find ourselves in a roadside pub.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It serves the purpose of drinking and diversion, and little more.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Solomon plays his violin, Brown and Hamilton perform a decent, paired magic routine before a SPARSE AUDIENCE NOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OF "SELECT CHARACTER."
{META_DATA}: 11.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 16 INT. PUB - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: After the show, the pub now fairly empty, Solomon, Hamilton and Brown sit down to eat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hamilton and Brown drink, but again Solomon abstains.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Though Solomon remains cool, Hamilton and Brown put up a great show of being disappointed as Hamilton counts out what little money was collected.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: Not an additional tip from a one of them.
{DIALOGUE}: They expect to be entertained for nothing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: And not satisfied a bit despite giving them more than what they paid for.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: It's the national mood.
{DIALOGUE}: There's too much grief to make room for frivolity.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: My sincerest apologies, Solomon.
{DIALOGUE}: You were promised opportunity, and you were given none.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: The opportunity is with the circus.
{DIALOGUE}: A two man show poorly promoted, what were we to expect?
{DIALOGUE}: But the circus bills itself.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: True.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: I have told you of the circus with which we are connected.
{DIALOGUE}: Creatures from the darkest of Africa.
{DIALOGUE}: Acrobats from the Orient who--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: You have described it, yes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: We need to return immediately to Washington.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon...I believe us familiar enough now, but forgive me if I am bold...would you consider making the trip with us?
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon gives a bit of a laugh at the idea.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 12.
{META_DATA}: 16 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: Entertaining at pubs and inns has it's place, but a man of your skills deserves better.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: Hear, hear.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: And more importantly you would build your own name and following.
{DIALOGUE}: The circus tends to attract those with the highest of reputations.
{DIALOGUE}: An introduction here and there could amount to a lifetime of reward.
{DIALOGUE}: Now would be the time.
{DIALOGUE}: With your family away, an opportunity presents itself.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: Said as fellow artists as well as businessmen.
{DIALOGUE}: Well worth the effort at least.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: You present a flattering representation.
{DIALOGUE}: As my family will be traveling back shortly, perhaps I might commit only to one trial engagement.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, very good, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: Very good.
{DIALOGUE}: I cannot recall being so excited.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: There is a practical concern.
{DIALOGUE}: If you are to continue on with us you should obtain your free papers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Not necessary.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: Here in New York, no.
{DIALOGUE}: But we will be entering slave states and as a matter of precaution... It's to all our benefit we should not have to come to account for your well being.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: Six shillings worth of effort could well save much trouble later.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 12A.
{META_DATA}: 16 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: We'll go to the Customs House in the morning, then travel on.
{DIALOGUE}: Good business all around.
{META_DATA}: 13.
{META_DATA}: 17 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 18 EXT. WASHINGTON - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The city is a swarm of people.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At the moment the populace is displaying both sorrow and anticipation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sorrow for the loss of the President.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Many are dressed in black, and black crepe hangs nearly everywhere.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Black armbands are frequently seen, and the occasional American Flag hung at half mast.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As well, there are portraits of Harrison at varying locations.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Having arrived in Washington, Solomon, Hamilton and Brown
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: RIDE ONWARD IN THEIR CARRIAGE.
{META_DATA}: 19
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GADSBY HOTEL/DINNING ROOM - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A decent though crowded, boisterous and smoke-filled joint.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Very lively.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon, Hamilton and Brown are among several parties drinking in the hotel's bar.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As with seemingly everywhere in the city black crepes accessorize the background.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Brown counts out $43.00 IN COIN on the tabletop.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon is astonished by the amount.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: Forty-three dollars.
{DIALOGUE}: All to you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: That...it's far more than my wages amount to.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: Consider the remainder an advance from the circus.
{DIALOGUE}: I cannot tell you...I honestly wish you had seen the expression of our director when I described your abilities.
{DIALOGUE}: He was fairly overcome with excitement.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: You should have invited him to sup with us.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: I did.
{DIALOGUE}: I did, but so many preparations before the company is to depart.
{META_DATA}: SOLOMON
{META_DATA}: GENTLEMEN--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: Tomorrow we shall prepare for our Washington debut.
{DIALOGUE}: But tonight, our thoughts are with the great man
{META_DATA}: (MORE) (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 13A.
{META_DATA}: 19 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: for whom this city prepared solemn memorial.
{DIALOGUE}: He has passed from the praise of men to receive the plaudit of his heavenly father.
{DIALOGUE}: A fine man has passed.
{DIALOGUE}: Let us remember him with a drink.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 14.
{META_DATA}: 19 CONTINUED: (2)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Both Hamilton and Brown hold up their tankards to drink.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon, a bit reluctantly, does the same.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: Cheers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: Another.
{DIALOGUE}: Our departed President deserves all the salutation we can imbibe.
{DIALOGUE}: Hamilton and Brown drink again, and Solomon does as well.
{META_DATA}: 20
{META_DATA}: OMIT
{META_DATA}: 21 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 22 EXT. ALLEY - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WE MAKE A HARD CUT to Solomon outside of the Pub, in an alley, with Brown and Hamilton in silhouette, back-lit by the street lights.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is violently ill, hunched over and retching horribly.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: That's all right Solomon.
{DIALOGUE}: No shame in it.
{DIALOGUE}: No shame at all.
{META_DATA}: 15.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: A23 INT. GADSBY HOTEL - STAIRCASE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hamilton and Brown help Solomon to lumber up the spiral staircase, passing the occasional bemused guest.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 23 INT. GADSBY HOTEL/SOLOMON'S ROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hamilton is placing a spittoon near Solomon's bed, where a prone and reeling Solomon lays.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hamilton sits on the bed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he strokes Solomon's sweaty face, Hamilton speaks sweetly.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: I'm afraid that Brown and I haven't brought you much luck.
{DIALOGUE}: But rough waters bring smooth sailing.
{DIALOGUE}: Eventually they do.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: ....So...so sorry...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: Shhh.
{DIALOGUE}: We won't hear it.
{DIALOGUE}: We won't.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: Let him sleep.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: Hmm.
{DIALOGUE}: A good night's sleep.
{DIALOGUE}: And tomorrow...tomorrow you will feel as well and refreshed as though the earth were new again.
{DIALOGUE}: Hamilton lingers a bit too long and a bit too close to Solomon for Brown's taste.
{DIALOGUE}: With more than a bit of
{META_DATA}: SIGNIFICATION:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BROWN
{DIALOGUE}: Hamilton!
{DIALOGUE}: Nothing more we can do for him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HAMILTON
{DIALOGUE}: Such is the pity.
{DIALOGUE}: Displaying an odd sort of disappointment, Hamilton slinks away from the bed.
{DIALOGUE}: He crosses to, and BLOWS OUT A CANDLE.
{DIALOGUE}: The room goes dark with a blackness more than night.
{DIALOGUE}: Brown and Hamilton exit.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon lays in the dark and moans.
{DIALOGUE}: His sounds becoming MORE AND MORE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: DISTRESSED.
{META_DATA}: 24
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BURCH'S DUNGEON - DAWN
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 16.
{META_DATA}: 24 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon stirs, then slowly awakes to his new circumstances.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He finds himself in a nearly lightless room about twelve feet square with walls of solid masonry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is a thick and well-locked door, a small window covered with iron bars and a shutter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The only furniture is a wood stool and an old fashioned, dirty box stove.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Solomon rises he sees that his HANDS are CUFFED - the chain running to a bolt in the ground - and his LEGS IN IRONS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At first Solomon is incredulous.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But that emotion is replaced first by fury and then panic.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He begins to pull on the chains, fight against them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He does so with increasing desperation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon flails about, the sounds of the steel chains whipping and beating against the masonry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He grunts and screams without regard as the cuffs and irons bite into his flesh, but he cannot pull himself free.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: After several minutes of intense effort, Solomon tires, slows, then finally he collapses.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And in this collapsed state he remains.
{META_DATA}: 25
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BURCH'S DUNGEON - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon again awakens.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He hears sounds beyond the door...footsteps.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eventually the door opens.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Enter JAMES BURCH - who runs the slave pen - and EBENEZER RADBURN who works as a turnkey and overseer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the door opens, this is the first light to seep into the otherwise near-black room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The shine is painful to Solomon's eyes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With no salutation whatsoever, Burch
{META_DATA}: ASKS:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BURCH
{DIALOGUE}: Well, my boy, how yah feel now?
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon rises up as best he can.
{DIALOGUE}: With all the resolve he can put together he states what he considers to be fact:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I am Solomon Northup.
{DIALOGUE}: I am a free man; a resident of Saratoga, New York.
{DIALOGUE}: The residence also of my wife and children who are equally free.
{DIALOGUE}: I have papers.
{DIALOGUE}: You have no right whatsoever to detain me--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BURCH
{DIALOGUE}: Yah not any--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: And I promise you - I promise - upon my liberation I will have satisfaction for this wrong.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BURCH
{DIALOGUE}: Resolve this.
{DIALOGUE}: Produce your papers.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 17.
{META_DATA}: 25 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With confidence Solomon goes to the pocket of his trousers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He searches one, then the other, but they are empty.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He feels quickly about himself, but clearly his papers have been lifted.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon's confidence shifts, but to resolve rather than fear.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Papers or none, he will not be easily cowed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still, Burch asserts:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BURCH (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Yah no free man.
{DIALOGUE}: And yah ain't from Saratoga.
{DIALOGUE}: Yah from Georgia.
{DIALOGUE}: A moment.
{DIALOGUE}: Not a word spoken among the trio, but Solomon and Burch do some serious eye fucking, neither man yielding.
{DIALOGUE}: Burch says again:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BURCH (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Yah ain't a free man.
{DIALOGUE}: Yah nuthin' but a Georgia runaway.
{DIALOGUE}: Burch waits for Solomon to acquiesce.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon does not in any way.
{DIALOGUE}: Both men exchange a long and daring stare.
{DIALOGUE}: The two are clearly at an intellectual stand off.
{DIALOGUE}: Burch, leans to Radburn, SAYS SOMETHING WHICH WE CANNOT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: DISTINGUISH.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Radburn walks off-camera and returns with a pair of "instruments:" a PADDLE - the flattened portion, which is about the size in circumference of two open hands, and bored with a small auger in numerous places.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He also carries a WHIP.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A cat-o-nine tails; a large rope of many strands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The strands unraveled and a knot tied at the extremity of each.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Burch says again:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BURCH (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Yah a runaway nigger from Georgia.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon stands with a quiet stoicism.
{DIALOGUE}: He will say nothing of the kind.
{DIALOGUE}: As that is the case, Solomon is seized by both men.
{DIALOGUE}: He is pulled over the bench, face downward, shirt still on his back.
{DIALOGUE}: Radburn then STEPS ON HIS CHAINS, holding Solomon down in a bent position.
{DIALOGUE}: With no preamble, Burch begins to beat Solomon about the back with the paddle.
{DIALOGUE}: Burch strikes him wordlessly - no taunting, no sneering.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon screaming against each blow.
{DIALOGUE}: His back immediately SWELLING WITH WELTS AND
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BRUISES.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This beating continues on and on and on until quite literally Burch WEARS HIMSELF OUT with the effort.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dripping in sweat and panting:
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 18.
{META_DATA}: 25 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BURCH (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Yah still insist yah a free man?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: ...I..
{DIALOGUE}: I insist... Burch regrets hearing this.
{DIALOGUE}: Not from sympathy, but rather because he's nearly too tired to go back to beating Solomon.
{DIALOGUE}: Yet, as if returning to work, Burch returns to pummeling Solomon.
{DIALOGUE}: Burch punctuates the blows
{META_DATA}: WITH:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BURCH
{DIALOGUE}: Yah a slave.
{DIALOGUE}: Yah a Georgia slave!
{DIALOGUE}: Burch continues to strike, and strike... This time until the paddle SNAPS IN HALF.
{DIALOGUE}: Burch then GRABS THE WHIP.
{DIALOGUE}: Hardly missing a stroke, he whips Solomon relentlessly, the flails cutting into Solomon's back.
{DIALOGUE}: Again, Burch's arm tires before Solomon "breaks."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BURCH (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Are yah slave?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: ...No... Burch goes back to whipping and whipping, and whipping...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SOLOMON'S BACK IS NOW TORN OPEN WITH LACERATIONS AND OOZING WITH BLOOD.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finally Burch can whip no more.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pours sweat and sucks air, leaving himself just enough energy to take up his instruments and EXIT.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Radburn lingers for a moment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He takes the irons off Solomon's legs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Opens the window some.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he makes these gestures, in a patronizing and confidential manner, one wrought with poor sincerity::
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RADBURN
{DIALOGUE}: I seen a good many of the black kind just where yah're.
{DIALOGUE}: Sick.
{DIALOGUE}: Make me sick.
{DIALOGUE}: Often times the situation was resolved, and I think; what was all the beatin' and abuse for?
{DIALOGUE}: Things end as they should, and the violence was for naught.
{DIALOGUE}: So why cause trouble when they ain't no cause for it?
{DIALOGUE}: Be of a cooperative nature, and things don't need be particularly unpleasant.
{META_DATA}: (BEAT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Or, yah can carry on like yah been, and I fear yah won't live to see Sunday next.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With that thought, Radburn exits.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon rests.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But to rest seems like giving in to defeat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He begins pulling
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 19.
{META_DATA}: 25 CONTINUED: (3)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: on his chains.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But for all his struggling, the chain loosens none.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon calls out:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Help me!
{DIALOGUE}: Someone help me!
{DIALOGUE}: If anyone at all hears him, they do not respond.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon continues his plaintive cry for assistance.
{META_DATA}: 26
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BURCH'S DUNGEON - CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Beginning with a TIGHT SHOT on the shuttered, barred window of Burch's dungeon - Solomon's cries barely eking beyond the space - THE CAMERA PULLS BACK from the building, onto the city until clearly visible is the Nation's capital.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's icon's of freedom - the WHITE HOUSE, the CAPITOL BUILDING - fairly mocking Solomon's captivity.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Simultaneously, barren at the early hour and cluttered with litter and the remains of previous day's procession, the city is a bleak and forboding sight.
{META_DATA}: 27
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BURCH'S DUNGEON - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: IT IS DAY NOW.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door to the yard is thrown open.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The harsh white light floods all over Solomon.
{META_DATA}: 28 OMITTED
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 20.
{META_DATA}: 28 CONTINUED:
{META_DATA}: 29 MOVED TO SC. A32
{META_DATA}: 21.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 30 EXT. BURCH'S DUNGEON/YARD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is a yard just beyond Burch's.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The yard is hemmed in by a brick wall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the yard are two men, and a boy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The oldest is CLEMENS RAY a man of about 25 years of age.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is well educated.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: JOHN WILLIAMS is about 20 years old.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is born and bred a slave, is lacking in education, and overwhelmed with fear of the situation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finally there is a child about 10 years of age who answers to the name of Randall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon, Clemens Ray, John and Randall ALL STAND NAKED.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Though they try to cover their privates a bit, they are all aware of the uselessness of modesty.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Radburn is present.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has before him A COUPLE OF BUCKETS OF COLD WATER.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He throws water on the naked men.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RADBURN
{DIALOGUE}: Go on.
{DIALOGUE}: Warsh up.
{DIALOGUE}: The men, soaking in humility as well as water, begin to scrub with A SINGLE BAR OF HARSH SOAP passed among them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RADBURN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: The boy, too.
{DIALOGUE}: Get him clean.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon takes some soap and rubs it over Randall.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RADBURN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Scrub now.
{DIALOGUE}: Git 'em clean.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon scrubs harder.
{DIALOGUE}: Randall - clearly cold and uncomfortable - appeals to Solomon.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RANDALL
{DIALOGUE}: Do you know when my Mama will come?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RADBURN
{DIALOGUE}: Hush him up!
{DIALOGUE}: Seeing Solomon has no answer for him, Randall begins to cry.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RANDALL
{DIALOGUE}: Mama .
{DIALOGUE}: Mama!
{DIALOGUE}: Is she going to come?
{DIALOGUE}: Doing all he can to spare the child from a certain
{META_DATA}: BEATING:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Quiet, please.
{DIALOGUE}: Randall is becoming nearly inconsolable.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RANDALL
{DIALOGUE}: Mama!
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 21A.
{META_DATA}: 30 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Saying anything to keep the boy quiet:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Your mother will come, I swear she will, but you must be silent.
{DIALOGUE}: Please.
{DIALOGUE}: Be silent!
{DIALOGUE}: On the seeming strength of Solomon's promise, Randall goes silent.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon looks to Radburn, who just throws water on the soapy men.
{META_DATA}: 22.
{META_DATA}: 31 OMITTED
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: A32 INT. BURCH'S DUNGEON - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Radburn brings food in to Solomon; a shriveled piece of meat and some water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Just barely enough to sustain Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Radburn also has a SHIRT.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RADBURN
{DIALOGUE}: That old thing of yours is just rags and tatters.
{DIALOGUE}: Need something proper to wear.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon doesn't move for the clothing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RADBURN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Go'won.
{DIALOGUE}: Put it on.
{DIALOGUE}: With slow defiance, Solomon does as instructed.
{DIALOGUE}: He removes what remains of his old shirt - the one he was wearing when first kidnapped - and puts on the one Radburn brought him.
{DIALOGUE}: The shirt's ill-fitting and dirty.
{DIALOGUE}: Despite that, Radburn says:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RADBURN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: There.
{DIALOGUE}: Tha's fine.
{DIALOGUE}: Tha's fine.
{DIALOGUE}: Got no gratitude?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: ...Thank you...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RADBURN
{DIALOGUE}: Yah keep bein' proper, yah'll see how things work out.
{DIALOGUE}: Radburn starts to take the old shirt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: No!
{DIALOGUE}: It was from my wife.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RADBURN
{DIALOGUE}: Rags and tatters.
{DIALOGUE}: Rags and tatters.
{DIALOGUE}: Taking the shirt, the "rags and tatters" as he calls them, Radburn exits, locking the door behind him.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon sits with the plate of food before him.
{DIALOGUE}: He pushes the plate away rather than eat.
{META_DATA}: 32
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BURCH'S DUNGEON/YARD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sitting together out in the yard are Clemens Ray, John and Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Over time they have drawn trustworthy enough to speak with one another.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At the moment Solomon is still trying to apply reason to the situation.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 22A.
{META_DATA}: 32 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Randall wanders about in the background.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As usual, he calls out for his "Mama."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: By now, however, his calls should feel like little more than background noise.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: This can't stand.
{DIALOGUE}: It is a crime.
{DIALOGUE}: I believe now someone lay in wait for me.
{DIALOGUE}: My drink was altered... We are free men.
{DIALOGUE}: They have...they have no right to hold us.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon waits for a response from the others.
{DIALOGUE}: They give none.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: We need a sympathetic ear.
{DIALOGUE}: If we have an opportunity to explain our
{META_DATA}: SITUATION--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLEMENS
{DIALOGUE}: Who in your estimation is that sympathetic ear?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: The two men I journeyed with.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm certain they're making inquires at this very moment.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLEMENS
{DIALOGUE}: I would be just as certain they are counting the money paid for delivering you to this place.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: They were not kidnappers.
{DIALOGUE}: They were artists.
{DIALOGUE}: Fellow performers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLEMENS
{DIALOGUE}: You know that?
{DIALOGUE}: You know for certain who they were?
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 23.
{META_DATA}: 32 CONTINUED: (2)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The fact is, Solomon can't say for certain.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLEMENS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: How I reckon the situation: whatever past we had...well, that's done now.
{DIALOGUE}: The reality to come is us being transported southward.
{DIALOGUE}: New Orleans if I were to venture.
{DIALOGUE}: After we arrive, we'll be put to market.
{DIALOGUE}: Beyond that... Well, once in a slave state I suppose there's only one outcome.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOHN
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLEMENS
{DIALOGUE}: I don't say that to give you empty agitation, John...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOHN
{DIALOGUE}: For y'all.
{DIALOGUE}: For y'all they ain't nothin' but that!
{DIALOGUE}: But John was'n kidnapped.
{DIALOGUE}: John bein' hold as debt, tha's all.
{DIALOGUE}: Massa pay his debt, and John be redeemed--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLEMENS
{DIALOGUE}: Boy, our masters will not come for us.
{DIALOGUE}: John is nearly beside himself with panic.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOHN
{DIALOGUE}: Now John's...John's sorry for y'all, but tha's how it be.
{DIALOGUE}: Where y'all goin', yah goin' witout John.
{DIALOGUE}: Massa take care of me.
{DIALOGUE}: Massa take care.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RANDALL
{DIALOGUE}: Mama!
{DIALOGUE}: All three men turn and look.
{DIALOGUE}: At the moment Randall doesn't call out emptily.
{DIALOGUE}: At the door to the yard is Burch along with two women.
{DIALOGUE}: One in her late twenties; ELIZA.
{DIALOGUE}: She is "arrayed in silk, with rings upon her fingers, and golden ornaments suspended from her ears."
{DIALOGUE}: Though a slave, Eliza was a mistress and has - to this point - lived well.
{DIALOGUE}: This is reflected in her airs and her speech.
{DIALOGUE}: The other is a little girl, light in skin color, of about seven or eight.
{DIALOGUE}: This is EMILY, Randall's half sister.
{DIALOGUE}: As she enters the yard Eliza squeals with high delight, then breaks into tears of both sorrow and joy.
{DIALOGUE}: Clearly this is mother and child being reunited.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 24.
{META_DATA}: 32 CONTINUED: (3)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Burch locks the yard door, Eliza clutches Randall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is overcome with emotion.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA
{DIALOGUE}: My darling.
{DIALOGUE}: My sweet, sweet baby.
{META_DATA}: 33
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BURCH'S DUNGEON - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Later in the evening.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon now shares his space with Eliza and her children.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the children rest, Eliza drops into a lament as if pleading her case to Solomon who lends a sympathetic ear.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Both slyly, and with a bit of aggrandizement:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA
{DIALOGUE}: When I say I had my master's favor, you understand.
{DIALOGUE}: Above even his own wife, I had it.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you know that he built a house for me?
{DIALOGUE}: Built it on the sole condition that I reside there with him.
{DIALOGUE}: The added promise in time I would be emancipated.
{DIALOGUE}: And for nine years he blessed me with every comfort and luxury in life.
{DIALOGUE}: Displaying the finery she still wears:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Silks and jewels and even servants to wait upon us.
{DIALOGUE}: Such was our life, and the life of this beautiful girl I bore for him.
{DIALOGUE}: But Master Berry's daughter...she always looked at me with an unkind nature.
{DIALOGUE}: She hated Emily no matter she and Emily were flesh of flesh.
{DIALOGUE}: As Master Berry's health failed, she gained power in the household.
{DIALOGUE}: Eventually, I was brought to the city on the false pretense of our free papers being executed.
{DIALOGUE}: If I had known what waited; to be sent south?
{DIALOGUE}: I swear I would not have come here alive.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 25.
{META_DATA}: 33 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eliza turns to her children:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: My poor, poor babies.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 34 INT. BURCH'S DUNGEON - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's the deep of night, all are sleeping.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A KEY TURNS IN THE LOCK AND THE DOOR OPENS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Burch enters with Radburn beside him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Both carry LANTERNS with them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hardly giving Solomon and Eliza a moment to rouse themselves,
{META_DATA}: BURCH DEMANDS:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BURCH
{DIALOGUE}: Come on.
{DIALOGUE}: Get yer blankets.
{DIALOGUE}: Get up.
{DIALOGUE}: Sensing that things will not end well:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA
{DIALOGUE}: No, please don't...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BURCH
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want to hear yer talk.
{DIALOGUE}: Get in the yard.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA
{DIALOGUE}: Please...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RADBURN
{DIALOGUE}: Ain't no need for all that.
{DIALOGUE}: Putting hand to Randall's head.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RADBURN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Jus takin' a li'l trip, tha's all.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't want to frighten the chil'ren none over a li'l boat ride, do yah?
{DIALOGUE}: Eliza gives a shake of her head to the negative.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RADBURN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Alright then.
{DIALOGUE}: Git yerselves up.
{META_DATA}: 35
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BURCH'S DUNGEON/YARD - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We now have Solomon, Clemens, John, Eliza and the children.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are being cuffed together.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As John is cuffed, he pulls back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Scared.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He beings in
{META_DATA}: DESPERATION:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOHN
{DIALOGUE}: John's massa gunna pay his debt.
{DIALOGUE}: John's massa gunna come for him.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 26-28.
{META_DATA}: 35 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Not wanting to hear any of this talk, Burch strikes John several times in the head with a sap-like instrument.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Weakened, but again:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JOHN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: John's massa gunna-- Burch again strikes John until he's quiet.
{DIALOGUE}: Curiously, Emily and Randall don't even flinch.
{DIALOGUE}: Why would they?
{DIALOGUE}: They are quite used to seeing this kind of violence.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BURCH
{DIALOGUE}: Not a word out of none a yah.
{DIALOGUE}: Not a word.
{DIALOGUE}: Burch and Radburn begin driving the shackled slaves from the yard.
{META_DATA}: A36
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. BURCH'S DUNGEON/INT. WAGON/FLAT BED - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves are lead to a flat bed of the horse and carriage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are made to lay down side-by-side.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We stay with them as some sort of cloth is flung over them, obscuring and blacking out their view.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At that moment, the screen is BLACKENED and we hear the sound of the cart moving in haste.
{META_DATA}: 36
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. WASHINGTON, D.C. DOCK - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Led by Burch, the group of slaves arrive to a dock.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are taken quickly up a gangplank and onto the steamboat ORLEANS as the CAPTAIN, CREW and a MULATTO WOMAN WATCH, but do not interfere.
{META_DATA}: 37
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. ORLEANS/HOLD - CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves are hustled down one at a time into a dark, dank hold among barrels and boxes of freight...and RATS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Burch comes around and "checks" the chains; makes sure they are all secure and locked.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Satisfied, he heads up out of the hold.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Radburn follows.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Alone in the dark in the hold, John cries, as does Eliza.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon stares down Burch for as long as he can, as if wishing bad things.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As if wanting to exact some measure of revenge.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But the greater insult is that Burch and Radburn, engaged in conversation, take no notice of Solomon whatsoever.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is that insignificant to them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: That fact, that reality, makes Solomon boil with a rage he cannot express in words.
{META_DATA}: 38
{META_DATA}: OMIT
{META_DATA}: 26-28A.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 38A INT. STEAMBOAT - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We are now in the engine room of the steamboat, pistons pumping, black oily cogs turning, the power and the rhythm are both aggressive and hypnotic.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A shovel comes into view, feeding the furnace.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 38B EXT. SEA - DUSK/DAWN
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The steamboat is en route between Washington and Norfolk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We tilt up from the violent water foam to the powering paddles of the boat.
{META_DATA}: 39 MOVED TO 43A
{META_DATA}: 29.
{META_DATA}: 40 OMIT
{META_DATA}: 41 OMIT
{META_DATA}: 42 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 43 INT. ORLEANS/HOLD - LATER - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Down in the hold the slaves eat, pray.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The MULATTO WOMAN moves among them, catching ELIZA's eye.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MULATTO WOMAN
{DIALOGUE}: Cheer up and don't be so cast down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clemens Ray and Solomon watch as the Mulatto Woman returns to top deck, the trapdoor locked firmly behind her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clemens Ray turns to Solomon with a deadpan stern expression.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLEMENS RAY
{DIALOGUE}: If you want to survive, do and say as little as possible.
{DIALOGUE}: Tell no one who you really are and tell no one that you can read and write.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 30.
{META_DATA}: 43 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clemens Ray turns away from Solomon, eyes lost into the distance.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLEMENS RAY (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (SLOWLY)
{DIALOGUE}: Unless you want to be a dead nigger.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon's face is one of a confused despair.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 43A EXT. NORFOLK/PORT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see a flat overhead view of the port of Norfolk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sardines are laid out to dry in rows, glittering in the day's sun as if like silver pennies.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A chain of slaves enter the frame and are led one by one on to the docked vessel.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MORE SLAVES - about 15 in all, of various genders and ages - are brought on board.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chief among them is ROBERT who fights viciously with his captors.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: "With all haste" is shoved down into the hold.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Having taken their cargo as far as they care or need to, Burch and Radburn depart.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They do so without a word spoken to Solomon or the others.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With this new and sizable batch of slaves on board, the crew again CASTS OFF, and the Orleans makes its way again.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 44 INT. ORLEANS/GALLEY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon is back cleaning in the galley.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he cleans, he again watches Robert prep food.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Robert's skill with a knife is not lost on Solomon.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 45 INT. HOLD - LATER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The hold is packed tighter now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Muzzle covering his face, Robert is shackled with his hands tied behind his back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon and Clemens Ray look on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A sailor descends the staircase and takes off Robert's muzzle, shooting him a forbidding look.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He leaves.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 31.
{META_DATA}: 45 CONTINUED:
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon, Clemens Ray and Robert, now in mid-conversation.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{DIALOGUE}: I say we fight.
{DIALOGUE}: Robert delivers this in a hushed voice.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: The crew is fairly small.
{DIALOGUE}: If it were well planned, I believe they could be strong armed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLEMENS RAY
{DIALOGUE}: Three can't stand against a whole crew.
{DIALOGUE}: The rest here are niggers, born and bred slaves.
{DIALOGUE}: Niggers ain't got the stomach for a fight, not a damn one.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ROBERT
{DIALOGUE}: All I know, we get where we travelling we'll wish we'd died trying.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLEMENS RAY
{DIALOGUE}: Survival is not about certain death, it is about keeping your head down.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon looks at Clemens Ray, agitated -- his voice now raised above the previous whispers.
{DIALOGUE}: Grits his teeth.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Days ago I was with my family, in my home.
{DIALOGUE}: Now you tell me all is lost.
{DIALOGUE}: "Tell no one who I really am" if I want to survive.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want to survive, I want to live.
{META_DATA}: 46 OMIT
{META_DATA}: 47 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 47A EXT. SEA - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The steamboat paddles pound the water, filling the whole frame.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The vessel ploughs on south.
{META_DATA}: 32.
{META_DATA}: 48 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 48A INT. HOLD - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves are asleep.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A Sailor descends the ladder approaching Eliza.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He bends down and attempts to wake the daughter by caressing her face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon rouses, and looks across to witness the scene.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From his vantage point, we see Eliza stand to interrupt the Sailor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Sailor looks at Eliza, Eliza looks back at him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Knowingly she leads him off into a corner of the hold.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As she does so, Eliza passes Robert who jumps up to stand between Eliza and the Sailor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stretching out a firm hand to the sailor's shoulder, Robert's look says "No you don't."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clemens Ray is awake now, watching.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is an odd moment of stillness between the Sailor and Robert, an impasse.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We focus on the Sailor's face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Slowly, a greasy smile erupts upon it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Back now to Robert's face, a look of incomprehension.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Robert looks down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We follow his gaze to the knife that has already been jabbed unseen between Robert's ribs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sailor withdraws the bloody blade.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A wide shot of the two men.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Robert collapses to the floor like a sack of potatoes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clemens Ray and Solomon react.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Complete horror.
{META_DATA}: 49 OMIT
{META_DATA}: 50 OMIT
{META_DATA}: 33.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 51 EXT. ORLEANS/DECK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We are back up on the deck of the ship.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SOLOMON AND CLEMENS RAY dump ROBERT's body over the side of the ship.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon watches as the body churns for a moment in the wake of the vessel... then sinks beneath the water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clemens Ray, with no sentimentality:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLEMENS RAY
{DIALOGUE}: Better off.
{DIALOGUE}: Better than us.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 51A EXT. NEW ORLEANS HARBOUR - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon's POV from the back of the steamship of Robert's corpse slipping gracefully into the water.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 52 EXT. NEW ORLEANS/PORT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -MID MAY, 1841- A white male, fairly smart, with broad shoulders, stands
{META_DATA}: AND BELLOWS-
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAY
{DIALOGUE}: Clemens...!
{DIALOGUE}: Clemens Ray!
{DIALOGUE}: We are in the port of New Orleans, one of the busiest in the young nation.
{DIALOGUE}: On the dock itself there is a bustle of activity as goods are loaded and unloaded from a various ships.
{DIALOGUE}: It's a bit of controlled chaos as a VARIETY OF LANGUAGES are spoken and shouted while slaves are shuttled from the Orleans to a holding pen.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon, and all the slaves are overwhelmed by all that is happening around them.
{DIALOGUE}: Two men - among many - are awaiting the arrival of the Orleans.
{DIALOGUE}: They are JONUS RAY - Clemens Ray's master - and DAVIS who is the solicitor of Mr. Ray.
{DIALOGUE}: They both look like they mean business.
{DIALOGUE}: The moment the gangplank is laid, Ray yells for Clemens.
{DIALOGUE}: Clemens, seeing his master, is nearly crazy with delight.
{DIALOGUE}: He is, uncharacteristically beside himself.
{DIALOGUE}: Ironically, his master now represents "freedom."
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 34.
{META_DATA}: 52 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CLEMENS
{DIALOGUE}: ...My master... Master Ray, sir!
{DIALOGUE}: Master Ray!
{DIALOGUE}: Clemens pulls on his chain.
{DIALOGUE}: As he does so, Several other slaves collapse in his effort to reach his master, like dominos.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAY
{DIALOGUE}: Who is in charge of this vessel?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CAPTAIN
{DIALOGUE}: I am the Captain.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAY
{DIALOGUE}: I am Mr. Jonus Ray.
{DIALOGUE}: My solicitor has documentation verifying that the Negro named Clemens Ray is my property.
{DIALOGUE}: As he reads PAPERS handed to him by Davis:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CAPTAIN
{DIALOGUE}: I know nothing of--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAY
{DIALOGUE}: You are ordered by court to return that property immediately, or face charges of thievery.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CAPTAIN
{DIALOGUE}: My duty is to transport goods.
{DIALOGUE}: I am not responsible for their origin.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAY
{DIALOGUE}: Remove these contraptions!
{DIALOGUE}: To his mate:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CAPTAIN
{DIALOGUE}: Free him!
{DIALOGUE}: Biddee does as ordered.
{DIALOGUE}: Once free, Clemens hugs and sobs over his master as would a lost and then found child.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAY
{DIALOGUE}: It's all well, now, Clemens.
{DIALOGUE}: You will return home with me.
{META_DATA}: (to the Captain)
{DIALOGUE}: Consider this notice and warning.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 35.
{META_DATA}: 52 CONTINUED: (2)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ray, Davis and Clemens head away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon seems both desperate and hopeful of some aid from Clemens and Ray.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But there is none forthcoming.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ray and Clemens continue on - Clemens not so much as even looking back in Solomon's direction.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon stands and watches as they fade into the environs and are gone from sight.
{META_DATA}: 53
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. NEW ORLEANS/PORT - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hours later.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves sit off on one side of the dock, baking in the sun, awaiting their fate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THEOPHILUS FREEMAN - a tall, thin-faced man with light complexion and a little bent - moves along the deck calling out names from a list.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves STAND as they are called.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: Oren.
{DIALOGUE}: John.
{DIALOGUE}: Lethe.
{DIALOGUE}: Eliza.
{DIALOGUE}: Randall.
{DIALOGUE}: Emily.
{DIALOGUE}: Platt... Platt!
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon does not respond.
{DIALOGUE}: Freeman looks around.
{DIALOGUE}: He spots Solomon.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Captain, who shipped that nigger?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CAPTAIN
{DIALOGUE}: Burch.
{DIALOGUE}: Freeman steps to Solomon.
{DIALOGUE}: He gives him a looking over.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: Stand up.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon does as told.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: You fit the description given.
{DIALOGUE}: Why didn't you answer when called?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: My name is not Platt.
{DIALOGUE}: My name is-- Freeman strikes Solomon hard across the face.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: Your name is Platt, and I will teach you your name so that you don't forget.
{META_DATA}: (to the Captain)
{DIALOGUE}: Shackle my niggers.
{DIALOGUE}: Get them to my cart.
{META_DATA}: 36.
{META_DATA}: 54 I/E. CART - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon is carted off along with the rest of "Burch's stock:" Eliza and her children, John and Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they move off from the port in a make-shift cart, it opens up to the frenzic, busy port.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For the first time Solomon sees true and severe slavery.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: These are not visiting servants, such as Jasper was back in Saratoga.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: These are humans held in strict bondage - herded like cattle, chained together as if in a "chain gang."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Slaves are evident not merely by the color of their skin.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The residue and accessories of slavery are everywhere.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Blacks almost universally display scars -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THICK AND HEAVY DEAD TISSUE FROM LACERATIONS LEFT UNTREATED - brands, and are often missing limbs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Blacks are held in all types of shackles, from simple chains to elaborate bindings, to neck collars that are spiked.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Some are muzzled or forced to wear bits.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One slave is attacked by a dog and the slave owner.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The dog pulls and tears at the slave's clothes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THESE IMAGES SHOULD BE A
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CONSTANT AND CONTINUAL CANVAS TO THE PIECE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: EVER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PRESENT, BUT NOT REALLY COMMENTED ON AS THEY ARE THE NORM.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They should be a reminder that not only are people being oppressed, but that there is an entire system of oppression in place.
{META_DATA}: 55
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FREEMAN'S SLAVE PEN - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: "Burch's stock:" arrive at Freeman's slave pen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are led in by Freeman and his house slave CAPE - a mulatto.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The yard is enclosed by plank, standing upright, with ends sharpened instead of brick walls as with Burch's.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Including Burch's group there are about 30 SLAVES in the pen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon and the others look around and see nothing but downtrodden and despondent faces.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Three men sit next to each other with muzzles and quietly stare back at this new batch of arrivals.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One attempts to speak, but all that comes out is a muffled, unintelligible sound.
{META_DATA}: 56
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FREEMAN'S SLAVE PEN - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves are in various states of undress, men and women alike.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They clean themselves, scrubbing with soap and water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Women wash their hair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Men shave, skin is oiled.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Freeman walks among them, inspecting them as they primp themselves.
{META_DATA}: 57
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. FREEMAN'S SLAVE PEN - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves are given new clothes by Cape.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The men are given hat, coat, shirt, pants and shoes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The women
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 37.
{META_DATA}: 57 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: frocks of calico and handkerchiefs to bind about their heads.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 58 INT. FREEMAN'S/GREAT ROOM - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's an odd, ironic scene.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves are in a large and fairly ornate room within Freeman's house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAPE PLAYS A PAINFUL TUNE ON A FIDDLE - background music - as Freeman tries to line up A SMALL GROUP OF THE SLAVES, he becomes less patient, jittery and nervous, knowing that his livelihood is at stake, he wants his slaves to make a good impression.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sometimes his patience gets the better of him, and his hands move freely in direction of the slaves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The business has the air of an etiquette class, though what Freeman is trying to do is coach the slaves into being more "sellable."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He works with them in groups of five or so.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: Tallest to smallest, understand?
{DIALOGUE}: Are you taller than her?
{DIALOGUE}: Then you'd go before her.
{DIALOGUE}: Do it.
{DIALOGUE}: Move.
{META_DATA}: (to the group)
{DIALOGUE}: Keep your heads up.
{DIALOGUE}: A sense of direction; that's how you look smart.
{DIALOGUE}: None of those saucer eyes.
{DIALOGUE}: Rid yourself of that smile.
{DIALOGUE}: Look like a goddamn grinnin' monkey.
{DIALOGUE}: Put the least thought in your head.
{DIALOGUE}: C'mon, now.
{DIALOGUE}: Think of somethin'.
{DIALOGUE}: Weary of Cape's playing, Solomon moves to Cape.
{DIALOGUE}: He asks:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Can you play a reel?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CAPE
{META_DATA}: (DISMISSIVE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nah.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: I don't know no reel.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: If I may...?
{DIALOGUE}: Cape looks to Freeman:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: He sick of your caterwaulin'.
{DIALOGUE}: Let him play, boy.
{DIALOGUE}: Let's see what he can do.
{DIALOGUE}: Cape reluctantly hands the fiddle over to Solomon.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon tunes it a bit, then begins to play.
{DIALOGUE}: His fingers stiff at first, he takes a moment to warm up.
{DIALOGUE}: But as he warms up he is, despite the circumstances, masterful.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 38.
{META_DATA}: 58 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE SLAVES ALL CLAP ALONG.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SOME DANCE ALONG.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All admire his work.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Freeman chief among them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Keep on.
{DIALOGUE}: Keep on.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon continues to play.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: A damn sight better than you, Cape.
{DIALOGUE}: A damn sight better.
{DIALOGUE}: Cape looks bitter as Solomon plays on.
{META_DATA}: 59
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. FREEMAN'S/GREAT ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We come in on an odd sort of sight; A JUMBLE OF ACTIVITY.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CUSTOMERS have come to see Freeman's lot - the room all gussied up with flowers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Freeman moves among them, displaying them as a rancher would prize chattel.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Freeman makes the slaves hold their heads up - "look smart" as he previously admonished them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are made to walk briskly back and forth while customers feel their hands and arms and bodies, turn them about and ask what skills they possess.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Customers routinely make the slaves open their mouths and show their teeth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At times a MALE or FEMALE SLAVE are taken off to the side, stripped and inspected more minutely.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One of them, John, is stripped and inspected.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cape, as he's done previously, plays his fiddle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A buyer - WILLIAM FORD; a man of middle age, and an attractive nature in his tone of voice - consults a list he's drawn up and asks of Freeman:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: What is the price for the ones Platt and Eliza?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: A thousand for Platt; he is a nigger of talent.
{DIALOGUE}: Seven hundred for Eliza.
{DIALOGUE}: My fairest price.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: You will accept a note?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: As always, from you, Mr. Ford.
{DIALOGUE}: Eliza is beside herself as it seems she is about to be separated from her family.
{DIALOGUE}: She begs of Ford:
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 39.
{META_DATA}: 59 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA
{DIALOGUE}: Please, sir... Please don't divide my family.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't take me unless you take my children as well.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: Eliza, quiet!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA
{DIALOGUE}: You will have the most faithful slave in me, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: The most faithful slave that has ever lived, but I beg that you do not separate us.
{DIALOGUE}: A BUYER interrupts the skirmish and approaches Freeman and delivers coolly, eyeing Randall-
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUYER
{DIALOGUE}: Your price for the child?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: You see how fit the boy is.
{DIALOGUE}: Like ripe fruit.
{DIALOGUE}: He will grow into a fine beast.
{DIALOGUE}: Randall is made to run, and jump by FREEMAN - exhibiting his activity and his condition.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Six hundred, and that's fair and final.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BUYER
{DIALOGUE}: Done.
{DIALOGUE}: He reaches into his waistcoat and retrieves his wallet, counting out six hundred dollars, placing them into the already extended hand of Freeman.
{DIALOGUE}: Ford sees the distress and panic in Eliza; it visibly touches him.
{DIALOGUE}: He now tries to buy EMILY to console her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: How much for the little girl?
{DIALOGUE}: You have no need for her.
{DIALOGUE}: One so young will bring you no profit.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: I will not sell the girl.
{DIALOGUE}: There's heaps 'n piles of money to be made off her.
{DIALOGUE}: She is a beauty.
{DIALOGUE}: One of the regular bloods.
{DIALOGUE}: None of your thick-lipped, bullet headed, cotton picking niggers.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 39A.
{META_DATA}: 59 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: Her child, man.
{DIALOGUE}: For God's sake, are you not sentimental in the least?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: My sentimentality stretches the length of a coin.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you want the lot, Mr. Ford, or do you pass on them all?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: I will take the ones Platt and Eliza.
{DIALOGUE}: Eliza grips her children tight.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA
{DIALOGUE}: I will not go without my children.
{DIALOGUE}: You will not take them from me.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 40.
{META_DATA}: 59 CONTINUED: (3)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As if to prove her wrong, Freeman puts a foot to Eliza and harshly kicks her away from Emily.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Please, don't.
{DIALOGUE}: No!
{DIALOGUE}: Freeman, to Cape:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: Take her out of here.
{DIALOGUE}: Cape DROPS HIS FIDDLE, begins to pull Eliza away toward the door of the room, but her screaming and pleading do not abate.
{DIALOGUE}: IT IS CLEARLY UNSETTLING TO THE OTHER BUYERS.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Keep her quiet.
{DIALOGUE}: Cape tries to muzzle her with his hand, but Eliza continues to scream for her children as Emily does for her mother.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EMILY
{DIALOGUE}: Mama... Mama!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN
{META_DATA}: (TO SOLOMON)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Play something!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Get the fiddle and play.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As ordered, Solomon takes up Cape's fiddle and begins to play lightly.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Play!
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon plays harder and more loudly.
{DIALOGUE}: Still, it is barely enough to drown out Eliza's cries.
{DIALOGUE}: Freeman gets the other slaves to clap along with Solomon's playing.
{DIALOGUE}: Emily frees herself and runs back, crying but endeavoring to be strong-
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EMILY
{DIALOGUE}: Don't cry, Mama.
{DIALOGUE}: I will be a good girl.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't cry.
{DIALOGUE}: I will keep my head up and I will look smart.
{DIALOGUE}: I will always look smart.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FREEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: Make merry, all of you!
{DIALOGUE}: Goddamn it, Cape!
{DIALOGUE}: Keep her quiet or it's your damned hide I will take it out of!
{DIALOGUE}: Cape pulls a rag, stuffs it in Eliza's mouth.
{DIALOGUE}: Clamping both hands over her mouth, he hauls Eliza from the room by the head.
{DIALOGUE}: IT IS AN UGLY, UGLY SCENE.
{META_DATA}: 40A.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 60 EXT. FORD PLANTATION - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Driven in a horse drawn wagon by Ford are Solomon and Eliza.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eliza is sullen to say the least.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With the loss of her two children she has dropped into a depression she will not be able to pull out of.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 41.
{META_DATA}: 60 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They arrive to the FORD PLANTATION.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The main house of the plantation - the GREAT HOUSE as they are commonly called - is sizable.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two stories high with a piazza in front.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the rear are also a log kitchen, poultry house, corncribs and several slave cabins.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The plantation is described as "a green spot in the wilderness."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With the arrival of Master Ford there is a flurry of activity - the "excitement" of a new delivery.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MR. CHAPIN, a white overseer, instructs a slave named SAM.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHAPIN
{DIALOGUE}: Sam, call to the Mistress.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM
{DIALOGUE}: Mistress!
{DIALOGUE}: Mistress, they arrivn'.
{DIALOGUE}: MISTRESS FORD EXITS the house - along with her attending slave, RACHEL, who is a cook AS WELL AS SAM'S WIFE - and travels to her husband, kisses him, then laughingly
{META_DATA}: INQUIRES:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MRS. FORD Did you bring all those niggers?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Two of them?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: You got two?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: Make me something to eat, dear.
{DIALOGUE}: The day has taken it from me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MRS. FORD Let me get a look at them...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Chapin--
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MRS. FORD
{META_DATA}: (RE: ELIZA)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This one's cryin'.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Why is this one cryin'?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: Separated from her children.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MRS. FORD Oh, dear.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: It couldn't be helped.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MRS. FORD Poor, poor woman.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Chapin, tomorrow you will take these two up to the mill and start them workin'.
{DIALOGUE}: For now make them
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 42.
{META_DATA}: 60 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: adequate; fix them a meal, and have them rest themselves.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHAPIN
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir.
{META_DATA}: (to the slaves:)
{DIALOGUE}: C'mon, now.
{DIALOGUE}: C'mon.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't dawdle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MRS. FORD
{META_DATA}: (TO ELIZA:)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Something to eat and some rest; your children will soon enough be forgotten.
{META_DATA}: A61A A61A
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FORD'S WORK AREA - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: John Tibeats, stands before the slaves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chapin hovers to one side.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: My name is John Tibeats, William Ford's chief carpenter.
{DIALOGUE}: You will refer to me as Master.
{DIALOGUE}: Tibeats nods in Chapin's direction:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Mister Chapin is the overseer on this plantation.
{DIALOGUE}: He is responsible for all of Ford's property.
{DIALOGUE}: You too will refer to him as Master.
{DIALOGUE}: This plantation covers many hundreds of acres, and you will traverse the Texas road between the forest site and the sawmill in double time.
{DIALOGUE}: Any clever nigger on that path that gets a little lightfooted, I will remind him that on one side men and bloodhounds patrol the border and on the other the bayou provides a hard living, with alligators and little to eat or drink that won't kill you.
{DIALOGUE}: No slave has escaped here with his life.
{DIALOGUE}: You're here to work niggers, so let's commence.
{DIALOGUE}: Tibeats begins to sing the song "Run Nigger, Run" mockingly.
{DIALOGUE}: We cut to Solomon chopping logs and into the montage of the slaves doing manual labor and arriving back to the sawmill.
{DIALOGUE}: Lyrics for "Run Nigger, Run"
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 42A.
{META_DATA}: A61A CONTINUED: A61A
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Oh run nigger run well the pattyroller will get you Run nigger run well you better get away Run nigger run well the pattyroller will get you Run nigger run well you better get away Nigger run nigger flew Nigger tore his shirt in two Run run the pattyroller will get you Run nigger run well you better get away Nigger run, run so fast Stoved his head in a hornets nest Run nigger run well the pattyroller will get you Run nigger run well you better get away Nigger run through the field Black slick coal and barley heel Run nigger run the pattyroller will get you Run nigger run well you better get away Some folks say a nigger won't steal I caught three in my corn field One has a bushel?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And one has a peck One had a rope and it was hung around his neck Run nigger run well the pattyroller will get you Run nigger run well you better get away Run nigger run well the pattyroller will get you Run nigger run well you better get away Oh nigger run and nigger flew Why in the devil can't a white man chew Run nigger run well the pattyroller will get you Run nigger run well you better get away Hey Mr. Pattyroller don't catch me Catch that nigger behind that tree Run nigger run well the pattyroller will get you?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Run nigger run well you better get away Nigger run, run so fast Stoved his head in a hornets nest Run nigger run well the pattyroller will get you Run nigger run well you better get away
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 61 EXT. WOODS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -END OF MAY THROUGH EARLY JUNE, 1841- We are in a wooded area.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is A GANG OF SLAVES chopping trees into timber.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is hard, laborious work made no more easy by the sweltering heat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon is among them as well as Sam.
{META_DATA}: 62
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. WOODS - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves now load the timber onto a horse drawn wagon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Again, hard work done under the ever present sun.
{META_DATA}: 42B.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 63 EXT. ROAD - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Sam drives the wagon, the other slaves trudge along side by foot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We should get the sense the travel is long and tedious.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 64 EXT. FORD'S WORK AREA - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is a sizable work area on the edge of Indian Creek.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is much work being done, the slaves primarily employed in piling the timber and chopping it into lumber.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As before, there is little doubt about the rigors of the job at hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Working as a carpenter at the work area is JOHN TIBEATS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There are also various CUSTOMERS who move about placing orders.
{META_DATA}: 65
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FORD PLANTATION - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -EARLY TO MID JUNE, 1841- It's Sunday morning.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All of Ford's slaves are dressed with their "finest" clothes - brightly colored and as free as possible of defect.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves are gathered on
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 43.
{META_DATA}: 65 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: the lawn just beyond the piazza.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mistress Ford is present as well.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the slaves listen, Ford reads to them Scripture.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His tone is of a man trying to preach by way of compassion.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: "But as touching the resurrection of the dead, have ye not read that which was spoken unto you by God, saying, I am the God of Abraham, and the God of Isaac, and the God of Jacob.
{DIALOGUE}: God is not the God of the dead, but of the living.
{DIALOGUE}: And when the multitude heard this, they were astonished at his doctrine.
{DIALOGUE}: Then one of them, which was a lawyer, asked him a question, tempting him, and saying, Master, which is the great commandment in the law?
{DIALOGUE}: Jesus said unto him, Thou shalt love the Lord thy God with all thy heart, and with all thy soul, and with all thy mind.
{DIALOGUE}: This is the first and great commandment.
{DIALOGUE}: And the second is like unto it, thou shalt love thy neighbor as thyself.
{DIALOGUE}: On these two commandments hang all the law and the prophets."
{DIALOGUE}: Despite the lightness with which Ford speaks and the hope in his words, ELIZA SITS OFF TO THE SIDE - SELF-SECLUDED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A BIT - WEEPING GENTLY.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We should be able to see in Mistress Ford's eyes that Eliza's constant crying is unsettling.
{META_DATA}: 66
{META_DATA}: OMITTED
{META_DATA}: 67 OMIT
{META_DATA}: 68 OMITTED
{META_DATA}: 44.
{META_DATA}: 69 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 70 EXT. FORD'S WORK AREA - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -MID JUNE, 1841- The slaves have broken for lunch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They snack on smoked meat and drink water from gourds.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they lunch Solomon reads from Sam's Bible to the other slaves.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: But he that is greatest among you, let him be as the younger; and he that is chief, as he that doth serve.
{DIALOGUE}: For whether is greater, he that sitteth at meat, or he that serveth?
{DIALOGUE}: Is not he that sitteth at meat?
{DIALOGUE}: But I am among you as he that serveth.
{DIALOGUE}: A white customer - WINSLOW - irate at the sight and sound of slaves reading Scripture, crosses over.
{DIALOGUE}: He grabs the Bible.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: From where did you thieve this?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM
{DIALOGUE}: Suh, the book is my property.
{DIALOGUE}: The White Customer has no interest in Sam's answer.
{DIALOGUE}: With flailing hands he STARTS BEATING ON SAM.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon tries to stop him.
{DIALOGUE}: That only makes the situation worse, Solomon now the target of the man's ire.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: Take your hands from me!
{DIALOGUE}: Ford comes running over.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: What is the commotion?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: Your niggers are either brazen or rebellious.
{DIALOGUE}: This one was readin' Scripture, and this one claims it to be his.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: It is.
{DIALOGUE}: A gift from his Mistress.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: You condone this?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: I encourage it.
{DIALOGUE}: As a Christian I can do no less.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 45.
{META_DATA}: 70 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WINSLOW
{DIALOGUE}: You can do no worse, Ford.
{DIALOGUE}: A slave that reads is dangerous.
{DIALOGUE}: Winslow moves off.
{DIALOGUE}: He yells back at Ford:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WINSLOW (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: And the man who would allow a slave to read is unfit to own niggers!
{DIALOGUE}: Handing the Bible back to Sam, very matter of factly:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: Pay him no mind.
{DIALOGUE}: The word of God applies to all.
{DIALOGUE}: In that you may take comfort.
{META_DATA}: 71
{META_DATA}: OMITTED
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 72 EXT. ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sam is at the reigns of the wagon carrying the timber to Ford's WORK AREA.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Slaves trudge alongside, same as it ever was.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Only...it's not quite the same.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sam brings the wagon to a halt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He, and the slaves look up the road ahead of them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Standing in the middle of the road is a group of CHICKASAWS INDIANS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are in their "usual" dress of buckskin breeches and calico hunting shirts of fantastic colors, buttoned from belt to chin.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They have with them DOGS and HORSES.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They carry with them the carcass of a deer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The two groups stare at each other for a long moment.
{META_DATA}: 73
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FIELD - DUSK/END OF DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The groups of slaves and Chickasaws are now intermingled.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They "break bread" - actually they work on the carcass of the deer which is now roasting over a large fire.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As well the group share a smoke on a pipe.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One of the Chickasaws is playing a tune on an "INDIAN FIDDLE."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Chickasaws perform a customary dance; trotting after each other, and giving utterance to a guttural, sing-song noise.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves enjoy the respite from work, Solomon particularly taken by the music...if not entirely enthralled by it.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 46.
{META_DATA}: 73 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: After a bit, Solomon rights himself and heads from the group.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 74 EXT. RIVER BANK - CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon arrives to some tall grass at the edge of the river.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Lowering his trousers, SOLOMON SQUATS TO DEFECATE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he does, he stares out toward the flowing waters of Indian Creek.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: After a few moments, as though a thought far greater than relieving himself has come to him, Solomon stands and replaces his pants.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Oddly, Solomon stares out at the water as though he were a man possessed.
{META_DATA}: 75
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FORD'S WORK AREA - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Just beyond the WORK AREA Solomon speaks with Ford as Tibeats listens.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon is drawing in the dirt, making rough diagrams for Ford as he explains himself.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: The creek is plenty deep enough to sail, even with a boat full of load.
{DIALOGUE}: The distance from the WORK AREA to the point on the latter bayou is several miles by water fewer than land.
{DIALOGUE}: It occurs to me that the expense of the transportation would be materially
{META_DATA}: DIMINISHED--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: "Materially diminished?"
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: If we use the waterway.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: It's a scheme.
{DIALOGUE}: Plenty of engineers have schemed similarly.
{DIALOGUE}: The passes are too tight.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I reckon them at more than twelve feet at their most narrow.
{DIALOGUE}: Wide enough for a tub to traverse.
{DIALOGUE}: A team of niggers can clear it out.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: And you know what of transport and terra formin'?
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 47.
{META_DATA}: 75 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I labored repairing the Champlain canal, on the section over which William Van Nortwick was superintendent.
{DIALOGUE}: With my earnings I hired several efficient hands to assist me, and I entered into contracts for the transportation of large rafts of timber from Lake Champlain to Troy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{META_DATA}: (TO TIBEATS)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: I'll admit to being impressed even if you won't.
{META_DATA}: (TO SOLOMON)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Collect a gang, see what good you can do.
{META_DATA}: 76
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. CREEK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -END OF JUNE, 1841- WE HAVE A SERIES OF SCENES in which we see Solomon and a TEAM OF BLACKS working on the creek: CHOPPING TREES ALONG THE BANKS, widening out the shore... It's all just a trial for now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The work is diligent, but it is basic to this point.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still, under Solomon's direction, the slaves go at it like they've got something to prove.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And rightly they do.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon also works on a narrow raft of twelve cribs with which he will transport the timber.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Once this is constructed, HE PERSONALLY "SAILS" THEM UP
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE CREEK WITH A TEST LOAD.
{META_DATA}: 77
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FORD'S WORK AREA - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ford and a group of slaves wait along the river banks just beyond the WORK AREA.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All are expectant in their manner.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A long moment passes with no sign of Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then, from up river, we see Solomon's raft of lumber winding its way.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SLAVES CHEER, and Ford literally applauds the effort.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tibeats looks pissed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has just been shown up after all.
{META_DATA}: 78
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FORD PLANTATION/GREAT HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As we come into the scene, Ford is presenting Solomon with a fiddle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Not as grand as the one he previously owned in New York, but a fine instrument none the less.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is a gift of thanks for his hard work.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon's gratitude is easily expressed.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 48.
{META_DATA}: 78 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: My great thanks, Master Ford.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: My thanks to you, and it is the least of it.
{DIALOGUE}: My hope is that it brings us both much joy over the years.
{DIALOGUE}: Following the statement, Solomon's not sure how to react.
{DIALOGUE}: He remains grateful, but the thought of "over the years" is just a reminder of the altered state in which he now finds himself.
{META_DATA}: 79
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FORD PLANATION/SLAVE SHACK - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -END OF JULY, 1841- The slaves eat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All tired from a days work they conduct themselves in silence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All except for Eliza who, SLIPPING INTO PERMANENT DEPRESSION, as always weeps.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sound of her sobbing edging him up - particularly after Master Ford's "over the years" observation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon
{META_DATA}: FINALLY SNAPS:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Eliza.
{DIALOGUE}: Eliza, stop!
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon goes to her, grabs Eliza.
{DIALOGUE}: She does not stop.
{DIALOGUE}: As if to force the misery from her, Solomon SHAKES ELIZA
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: VIOLENTLY.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Stop it!
{DIALOGUE}: Stop!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA
{DIALOGUE}: It's all I have to keeps my loss present.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: You let yourself be overcome by sorrow.
{DIALOGUE}: You will drown in it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA
{DIALOGUE}: Have you stopped crying for your children?
{DIALOGUE}: You make no sounds, but will you ever let them go in your heart?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: ...They are as my flesh...
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 49.
{META_DATA}: 79 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA
{DIALOGUE}: Then who is distressed?
{DIALOGUE}: Do I upset the Mistress and the Master?
{DIALOGUE}: Do you care less for my loss than their well being?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Master Ford is a decent man.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA
{DIALOGUE}: He is a slaver.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Under the circumstances--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA
{DIALOGUE}: Under the circumstances he is a slaver!
{DIALOGUE}: Christian only in his proclamations.
{DIALOGUE}: Separated me from my precious babies for lack of a few dollars.
{DIALOGUE}: But you truckle at
{META_DATA}: HIS BOOT--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: No...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA
{DIALOGUE}: You luxuriate in his favor.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I survive.
{DIALOGUE}: I will not fall into despair.
{DIALOGUE}: Woeful and crushed; melancholy is the yolk I see most.
{DIALOGUE}: I will offer up my talents to Master Ford.
{DIALOGUE}: I will keep myself hearty until freedom is opportune.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA
{DIALOGUE}: Ford is your opportunity.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you think he does not know that you are more than you suggest?
{DIALOGUE}: But he does nothing for you.
{DIALOGUE}: Nothing.
{DIALOGUE}: You are no better than prized livestock.
{DIALOGUE}: Call for him.
{DIALOGUE}: Call, tell him of your previous circumstances and see what it earns you...Solomon.
{DIALOGUE}: Eliza uses Solomon's name quite pointedly as if to underscore his true self.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon get her meaning.
{DIALOGUE}: Yet he says nothing.
{DIALOGUE}: Again, pointedly:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: So, you've settled into your role as Platt, then?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{META_DATA}: (DEFENSIVE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: My back is thick with scars from
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 50.
{META_DATA}: 79 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: protesting my freedom.
{DIALOGUE}: Do not
{META_DATA}: ACCUSE ME--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ELIZA
{DIALOGUE}: I accuse you of nothing.
{DIALOGUE}: I cannot accuse.
{DIALOGUE}: I too have done so many, many dishonorable things to survive.
{DIALOGUE}: And for all of them I have ended up here... No better than if I had stood up for myself.
{DIALOGUE}: Father, Lord and Savior forgive me... Forgive me.
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, Solomon, let me weep for my children.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: At the same time came the disciples unto Jesus, saying, Who is the greatest in the kingdom of heaven?
{META_DATA}: 80
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FORD PLANTATION - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -AUGUST, 1841- It's Sunday.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves are again gathered in the rose garden near the front of the house to hear the word of the Lord as read by Master Ford.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: And Jesus called a little child unto him, and set him in the midst of them, And said, Verily I say unto you, Except ye be converted, and become as little children, ye shall not enter into the kingdom of heaven.
{DIALOGUE}: The phrase seems to trigger Eliza's tears.
{DIALOGUE}: She begins to sob uncontrollably.
{DIALOGUE}: Mrs. Ford turns to Rachel in a hushed whisper-
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MRS. FORD I cannot have that kind of depression about.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon, pretending not to have heard, slowly turns to Eliza with worry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ford continues to preach over Eliza's keening.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: But whoso shall offend one of these little ones which believe in me, it were better for him that a millstone were hanged about his neck, and that he were drowned in the depth of the sea.
{DIALOGUE}: Woe unto
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 50A.
{META_DATA}: 80 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: the world because of offences!
{DIALOGUE}: For it must needs be that offences come; but woe to that man by whom the offence cometh!
{META_DATA}: BLACK
{META_DATA}: 51.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 81 EXT. FORD PLANTATION - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -JANUARY, 1842- Seasons have passed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is winter now, and very grey out along the bayou.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ford and Tibeats - who we have seen working around the WORK AREA - stand with Solomon, Tibeats giving Solomon an inspection.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ford carries much lament.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: Raise yer shirt.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon does as instructed.
{DIALOGUE}: Tibeats looks at Solomon's back, at the scars from lashings he bears.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Troublesome.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: He's a good carpenter and quick- witted.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: I am familiar with his cleverness.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: You won't find a nigger more humble.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: Ain't found a nigger yet I cain't humble.
{DIALOGUE}: Tibeats heads off.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon, highly curious over the preceding.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Sir, have I done something wrong?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: Not your concern, Platt.
{DIALOGUE}: I say with much...shame I have compiled debts.
{DIALOGUE}: I have long preached austerity, but find myself hypocritical in that regard.
{DIALOGUE}: You'll be in the ownership of Mr. Tibeats.
{DIALOGUE}: You are his now.
{DIALOGUE}: Serve him as you'd serve me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: And your faithfulness will not be forgotten.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 52.
{META_DATA}: 81 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: Pride and want have been my sin.
{DIALOGUE}: Loss of you is but one of my punishments.
{META_DATA}: 82
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FORD PLANATION - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -END OF JANUARY, 1842- [OVER ONE DAY] We see Solomon working as a carpenter, helping to erect a Weaving House that stands off to the side of the plantation's Great House.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At the moment Solomon is nailing on siding.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tibeats arrives and is immediately dissatisfied with the work.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: Make them boards flush.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: They are, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: They is no such thing.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon runs his hands over the boards.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: As smooth to the touch as a yearling's coat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: Callin' me a liar, boy?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Only a matter of perspective, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: From where you stand you may see differently.
{DIALOGUE}: But the hands are not mistaken.
{DIALOGUE}: I ask only that you employ all your senses before rendering judgement.
{DIALOGUE}: What's Tibeats to do when faced with fact?
{DIALOGUE}: All he can do is spew invectives.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: You are a brute.
{DIALOGUE}: You are a dog, and no better for followin' instruction.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I'll do as ordered, sir.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 53.
{META_DATA}: 82 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: Then you'll be up at daybreak.
{DIALOGUE}: You will procure a keg of nails from Chapin and commence puttin' on clapboards.
{DIALOGUE}: Tibeats wheels away.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon goes back to his work.
{DIALOGUE}: After a few moments Solomon notices a bit of commotion in the drive of the great house.
{DIALOGUE}: It involves an inconsolable Eliza who is being herded by Sam onto a cart DRIVEN BY A WHITE MAN.
{DIALOGUE}: Mistress Ford and Rachel watch.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon can only watch as the last connection to his days as a free man is driven away to a location unknown.
{META_DATA}: 83
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. WEAVING HOUSE - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is day break.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As ordered, Solomon is up and working.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chapin is rolling a keg of nails off a handcart for Solomon.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHAPIN
{DIALOGUE}: If Tibeats prefers a different size, I will endeavor to furnish them, but you may use those until further directed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir.
{META_DATA}: 84
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. WEAVING HOUSE - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the day gets on to mid-morning, the sun already baking in the sky, Tibeats makes his way over to Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Even before arriving to Solomon his mien is one of belligerence; out of sorts and something less than sober.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: I thought I told yah ta commence ta puttin' on clapboards this morn'.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 54.
{META_DATA}: 84 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, master.
{DIALOGUE}: I am about it.
{DIALOGUE}: I have begun on the other side of the house.
{DIALOGUE}: Tibeats walks around to look over Solomon's work.
{DIALOGUE}: He is picayune, as if purposefully looking for fault.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: Didn't I tell yah last night to get a keg of nails of Chapin?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: And so I did; and Chapin said he would get another size for you, if you wanted them when he came back from the field.
{DIALOGUE}: Tibeats walks to the keg and kicks it.
{DIALOGUE}: Moving toward Solomon "with a great passion:"
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: Goddamn yah!
{DIALOGUE}: I thought yah knowed somethin'!
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon, perhaps inspired by his moment with Eliza, is in no mood for Tibeats.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I did as instructed.
{DIALOGUE}: If there's something wrong, then its wrong with your instructions.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: Yah black bastard!
{DIALOGUE}: Yah goddman black bastard!
{DIALOGUE}: In an inconsolable rage, Tibeats runs off to the piazza to fetch a whip.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon looks around.
{DIALOGUE}: He is alone other than Rachel and Mistress Ford who, shocked by that which she witnesses, runs out to the field to fetch Chapin.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon's instinct is to run, but he stands his ground as Tibeats marches back whip in hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Strip yer clothes!
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon does no such thing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Strip!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I will not.
{DIALOGUE}: With "concentrated vengeance," Tibeats springs for Solomon, seizing him by the throat with one hand and
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 55.
{META_DATA}: 84 CONTINUED: (2)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: raising the whip with the other.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Before he can strike the blow, however, Solomon catches Tibeats by the collar of his coat and pulls him in close.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Reaching down, Solomon grabs Tibeats by the ankle and pushes him back with the other hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tibeats tumbles to the ground.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A violent struggle takes place as Solomon puts a foot to Tibeats throat, and then in a frenzy of madness snatches the whip from Tibeats and begins to strike him with the handle again and again and again.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: Yew will not live ta see another day, nigger!
{DIALOGUE}: This is yer last, I swear it!
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon ignores the threats, continues to beat Tibeats.
{DIALOGUE}: Blow after blow falling fast and heavy on Tibeats's wriggling form.
{DIALOGUE}: The stiff stock of the whip wraps around Tibeats's cringing body until Solomon's arm aches.
{DIALOGUE}: Tibeats's cries of vengeance turn to yelps for help and then pleas for mercy:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Murder!
{DIALOGUE}: It's murder!
{DIALOGUE}: Lord, God, help me.
{DIALOGUE}: God be merciful!
{DIALOGUE}: And then suddenly, Tibeats shrieks-
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Papa I'm sorry!
{DIALOGUE}: Chapin comes RIDING IN FROM THE FIELD fast and hard.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon strikes Tibeats a blow or two more, then delivers a well-directed kick that sends Tibeats rolling over the ground.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHAPIN
{DIALOGUE}: What is the matter?
{DIALOGUE}: Tibeats struggles up and tries to present an air of dignity and control while he keeps a demonic eye on
{META_DATA}: SOLOMON:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Master Tibeats wants to whip me for using the nails you gave me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHAPIN
{DIALOGUE}: What's the matter with the nails?
{DIALOGUE}: With a mix of shame, anger and embarrassment, Tibeats says, as if being exposed-
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: They're...they're too large.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHAPIN
{DIALOGUE}: I am overseer here.
{DIALOGUE}: I told Platt to use them, and
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 56.
{META_DATA}: 84 CONTINUED: (3)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHAPIN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I shall furnish such nails as I please.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you understand that, Mr. Tibeats?
{DIALOGUE}: Tibeats answer is in the grinding of his teeth and the shaking of his fist.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: This ain't done by half.
{DIALOGUE}: I will have flesh, and I will have all of it.
{DIALOGUE}: Tibeats moves off toward, and then INTO THE HOUSE.
{DIALOGUE}: Chapin follows.
{DIALOGUE}: A long moment, Solomon stands alone.
{DIALOGUE}: He looks around, not sure what to do; to stay or to flee.
{DIALOGUE}: Anxiety mounts on his features.
{DIALOGUE}: A moment more, and Tibeats EXITS the house.
{DIALOGUE}: He saddles his horse and rides off to beat the devil.
{DIALOGUE}: Or, worse, to fetch him.
{DIALOGUE}: Chapin comes running back out of the house.
{DIALOGUE}: He is visibly excited, and when he speaks he is quite earnest.
{DIALOGUE}: Though he tries to project reasoned emotions he gives off an air of impending trouble.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHAPIN
{DIALOGUE}: Do not stir.
{DIALOGUE}: Do not attempt to leave the plantation on any account whatever.
{DIALOGUE}: But if you run there is no protecting you.
{META_DATA}: SOLOMON
{META_DATA}: SIR--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHAPIN
{DIALOGUE}: If you run, Platt, there is no protecting you.
{DIALOGUE}: Rachel...!
{DIALOGUE}: Chapin runs off to join Rachel.
{DIALOGUE}: The two converse at a distance from Solomon, then they head off for the log kitchen.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon is now very much alone, and he waits for what is to come.
{DIALOGUE}: AND WE WAIT WITH HIM.
{DIALOGUE}: And we wait, and we continue to wait... Moment by moment, the dread of the unexpected mounts.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon's eyes begin to well.
{DIALOGUE}: He has beaten a white man, and he knows that death awaits him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A SLIGHT PRAYER TO THE HEAVENS BEGINS TO FORM IN HIS THROAT, but he is too choked up to fully speak it.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 57.
{META_DATA}: 84 CONTINUED: (4)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chapin has now returned to the piazza.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stands and watches, but does not move to Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon waits, and waits... WE HEAR THE SOUND OF DISTANT HOOFS which grow louder and louder in the manner of rolling thunder.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's Tibeats.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He returns with two accomplices; RAMSAY and COOK.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They carry with them large whips and a coil of rope.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: Tha's the one.
{DIALOGUE}: Tha's him.
{DIALOGUE}: Dismounting, they move with menace that is tinged with perverse pleasure and wordless malevolence.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon tries to fight back, but he is strong armed and tied by TIBEATS - his wrists, and then ankles bound in the same manner.
{DIALOGUE}: In the meantime the other two have slipped a cord within Solomon's elbows, running it across his back and tying it firmly.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon is then dragged toward a peach tree.
{DIALOGUE}: A lynching is in store.
{DIALOGUE}: The naked horror of it intensely palpable.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon looks toward the piazza, but Chapin is now gone.
{DIALOGUE}: Tears of fear flow down Solomon's cheeks.
{DIALOGUE}: He is on the verge of panic; a man heading toward his own execution, he begins to struggle and fight.
{DIALOGUE}: A rope goes around Solomon's neck, then is tossed over the branch of the tree.
{DIALOGUE}: The trio begin to hoist Solomon.
{DIALOGUE}: He gasps and gags as spittle flies from his mouth and the life is choked from him.
{DIALOGUE}: With suddenness, Chapin comes from the house brandishing a pistol in each hand - Colt Paterson .36 caliber "Holster" pistols with 9" barrels.
{DIALOGUE}: Chapin moves with determination toward the lynch mob.
{DIALOGUE}: He is sharp and matter of fact.
{DIALOGUE}: With the guns in hand, he really doesn't need to be much more demonstrative.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHAPIN
{DIALOGUE}: Gentlemen... Whoever moves that nigger another foot from where he stands is a dead man.
{DIALOGUE}: I am overseer of this plantation seven years, and in the absence of William Ford, my duty is to protect his interests.
{DIALOGUE}: Ford holds a mortgage on Platt of four hundred dollars.
{DIALOGUE}: If you hang him, he loses his debt.
{DIALOGUE}: Until that is canceled you have no claim to his life.
{DIALOGUE}: Directing his attention to Ramsay and Cook:
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 58.
{META_DATA}: 84 CONTINUED: (5)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHAPIN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: As for you two, if you have any regard for your own safety...I say, begone!
{DIALOGUE}: Ramsay and Cook don't need to be told twice.
{DIALOGUE}: The pistols Chapin's gripping make the situation real clear.
{DIALOGUE}: Without further word, they mount their horses and ride away.
{DIALOGUE}: Tibeats remains, and his anger with him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TIBEATS
{DIALOGUE}: Yah got no cause.
{DIALOGUE}: Platt is mine, and mine ta do with as I please.
{DIALOGUE}: Yah touch my property, I will 'ave yah strung up as well.
{DIALOGUE}: Tibeats mounts up and departs.
{DIALOGUE}: There is a surreal moment as Chapin's not sure what to do about Solomon.
{DIALOGUE}: He chooses to do nothing.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon is left dangling by the neck from the tree as Chapin calls to Sam in the
{META_DATA}: DISTANCE:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHAPIN
{DIALOGUE}: Sam!
{DIALOGUE}: Get the mule.
{DIALOGUE}: You must ride to Master Ford.
{DIALOGUE}: Tell him to come here at once without a single moment's delay.
{DIALOGUE}: Tell him they are trying to murder Platt.
{DIALOGUE}: Hurry, boy.
{DIALOGUE}: Bring him back if you must kill the mule to do so!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SAM
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, suh!
{DIALOGUE}: Sam mounts up and rides off, the mule demonstrating much speed.
{META_DATA}: 85
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FORD PLANATION - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: HOURS HAVE PASSED.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sun is now at its apex.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sight and smell of the red rose bush is more than vivid as Solomon remains tied and dangling exactly where he was left.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The scene is both tranquil and horrific.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Life on the plantation continues.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The OTHER SLAVES work in the field.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CHILDREN make their way playfully in the yard.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It should all underscore the fact that a black, hanging even partially from a tree, is nothing unusual in this time and space.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 59.
{META_DATA}: 85 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chapin walks back and forth with the pistols in his hands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clearly he fears Tibeats returning with more and better assistance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And yet, he does nothing to alleviate Solomon's suffering.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He heeds Tibeats words, and as though caught up in the middle of nothing more than a property dispute, he offers no further aid.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon's head lolls to one side.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks toward the sun.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The bright light flares off the leaves and branches of the tree from which Solomon hangs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The glare in Solomon's eyes offering him more pain than solace, but he cannot help but look upward.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he does, his eyes flutter between life and lifelessness...
{META_DATA}: 86
{META_DATA}: OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 87 EXT. FORD PLANATION - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon continues to hang.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: By now he is drenched in sweat, and nearly delirious with dehydration.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His lips dry and parched.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He may not die from hanging, but he may very well expire before the day is over.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eventually Rachel comes over - timidly, and as though she were acting contrary to orders - and offers a drink of water from a tin cup, pouring it in Solomon's mouth for him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She then takes a small hand towel and dabs at the water which clings to his lips.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rachel then retreats, and leaves Solomon to hang.
{META_DATA}: 88
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FORD PLANATION - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sun is just now arching for the horizon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon remains, as though his torture will not end.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ford, trailed by Sam, finally comes riding up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He dismounts, and moves swiftly over to Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With great heartache:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: Platt... My poor Platt.
{DIALOGUE}: Ford produces a blade and cuts Solomon loose.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon attempts to carry himself, but he cannot.
{DIALOGUE}: He falls to the ground and passes out.
{META_DATA}: 89
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. FORD PLANATION/GREAT HOUSE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As we come into the scene, Solomon lays on a blanket on the floor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eventually, his eyes flutter, then open.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is in the foyer of the Ford house.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he gets his bearings, he looks around the interior.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE SPACE IS HANDSOME, AND WELL DECORATED.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is sharp contrast to the bleak surroundings, shacks and dungeons Solomon has largely been accustom to during his time of slavery.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It will be the "first and last time such a sumptuous resting place was granted" during his twelve years of bondage.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 60.
{META_DATA}: 89 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon doesn't have much chance to luxuriate in his surroundings.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He hears a DOG BARKING just outside, and is unnerved.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Has Tibeats returned to finish what he started?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From a study, Master Ford appears with a gun in hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He goes to the door, opens it and looks outside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He can see nothing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Satisfied, Ford crosses back over to Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is frank with Solomon regarding the situation.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: I believe Tibeats is skulkin' about the premises somewhere.
{DIALOGUE}: He wants you dead, and he will attempt to have you so.
{DIALOGUE}: It's no longer safe for you here.
{DIALOGUE}: And I don't believe you will remain passive if Tibeats attacks.
{DIALOGUE}: I have transferred my debt to Edwin Epps.
{DIALOGUE}: He will take charge of you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{META_DATA}: (desperate, urgent)
{DIALOGUE}: Master Ford, you must know; I am not a slave.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: I cannot hear that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Before I came to you I was a freeman.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORD
{DIALOGUE}: I am trying to save your life!
{DIALOGUE}: And...I have a debt to be mindful of.
{DIALOGUE}: That, now, is to Edwin Epps.
{DIALOGUE}: He is a hard man.
{DIALOGUE}: Prides himself on being a "nigger breaker."
{DIALOGUE}: But truthfully I could find no others who would have you.
{DIALOGUE}: You've made a reputation of yourself.
{DIALOGUE}: Whatever your circumstances, you are an exceptional nigger, Platt.
{DIALOGUE}: I fear no good will come of it.
{META_DATA}: 90
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/BACK PORCH - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -END OF JANUARY, 1842- From the back porch, we come into the scene on EDWIN EPPS; a repulsive and coarse man.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His language gives speedy and unequivocal evidence that he has never enjoyed the advantages of an education.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 61.
{META_DATA}: 90 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Epps reads the Bible to his slaves, eight of them altogether.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ABRAM; a tall, older slave of about sixty years.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WILEY, who is forty eight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PHEBE, who is married to Wiley.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BOB and HENRY who are Phebe's children, EDWARD and PATSEY.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Patsey is young, just 23 years old...though in the era, 23 not as young as in the present day.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is the offspring of a "Guinea nigger," brought over to Cuba in a slave ship.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She nearly brims with unconversant sexuality.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MISTRESS EPPS, Epps's wife, is also present.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She sits with, holds quite lovingly, some SLAVE CHILDREN.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WITH THEM SHE IS VERY "MOTHERLY."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We also see Epps's overseer TREACH.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Treach constantly sports a LOADED PISTOL.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Though Epps reads the word of the Lord, he lacks the tone of compassion with which Ford read.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: "And that servant which knew his Lord's will...WHICH KNEW HIS LORD'S WILL and prepared not himself...PREPARED NOT HIMSELF, neither did according to his will, shall be beaten with many stripes..." D'ye hear that?
{DIALOGUE}: "Stripes."
{DIALOGUE}: That nigger that don't take care, that don't obey his lord - that's his master - d'ye see?
{DIALOGUE}: - that 'ere nigger shall be beaten with many stripes.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, "many" signifies a great many.
{DIALOGUE}: Forty, a hundred, a hundred and fifty lashes... That's Scripter!
{META_DATA}: 91
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/FIELD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -AUGUST, 1842-
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WE START THE SCENE WITH A PAIR OF BLACK HANDS picking cotton ferociously.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As we move out, we identify PATSEY, a 23 year old striking black woman.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The camera moves out again to a wider shot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This reveals several lines of slaves picking cotton, with Patsey way out in the lead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We cut to another pair of black hands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This time, revealing SOLOMON, clumsy and unskilled hands, picking cotton.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A lash bears down on him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is August, "cotton picking" season.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We are looking out over a cotton field in full bloom.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It presents a visual purity, like an immaculate expanse of light, new-fallen snow.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The cotton grows from five to seven feet high, each stalk having a great many branches
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 62.
{META_DATA}: 91 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: shooting out in all directions and lapping each other above the water furrow.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is a slave to each side of the row.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They have a sack around their necks that hangs to the ground, the mouth of the sack about breast high.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Baskets are placed at the end of the furrows.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Slaves dump their sacks of cotton in the baskets, then pick until their sacks are again filled.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARDS
{DIALOGUE}: Pick that cotton.
{DIALOGUE}: Move along now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE SOUNDTRACK TO THE SCENE IS NOTHING MORE THAN THE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: RUSTLE OF LABOR, THE MALE CICADAS BUGS "TYMBALS" IN THE HEAT and a SPIRITUAL SUNG BY THE SLAVES.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Despite the heat, there is no stopping for water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves are "driven" by Edward, who is himself "driven" by Treach.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: C'mon.
{DIALOGUE}: Drive dem niggers.
{DIALOGUE}: Edward moves among the slaves, applying the whip to them without regard.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Pick dat cotton.
{DIALOGUE}: Move along now, hear?
{META_DATA}: 92
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/GIN HOUSE - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The day's work is done.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves are now assembled in the gin house with their baskets of cotton which are being weighed by Treach.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is anxiety among the slave, the reason for which soon becomes apparent.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: Two hundred forty pounds for Bob.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: What yah got for James?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: Two hundred ninety five pounds.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Tha's real good, boy.
{DIALOGUE}: Tha's real good.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: One hundred eighty two pounds for Platt.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps does not look happy.
{DIALOGUE}: Treach says again:
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 63.
{META_DATA}: 92 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: One hundred eighty two.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: How much can even an average nigger pick a day?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: Two hundred pounds.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: This nigger ain't even average.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps pulls Solomon aside.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: Five hundred twelve pounds for Patsey.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Five hundred twelve.
{DIALOGUE}: Yah men folk got no shame lettin' Patsey out pick yah?
{DIALOGUE}: The day ain't yet come she swung lower than five hundred pounds.
{DIALOGUE}: Queen of the fields, she is.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: Two hundred six pou--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: I ain't done, Treach.
{DIALOGUE}: Ain't I owed a minute to luxuriate on the work Patsey done?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: ...Sir...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Damned Queen.
{DIALOGUE}: Born and bred to the field.
{DIALOGUE}: A nigger among niggers, and God give 'er to me.
{DIALOGUE}: A lesson in the rewards of righteous livin'.
{DIALOGUE}: All be observant ta that.
{DIALOGUE}: All!
{META_DATA}: (BEAT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Now, Treach.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Now speak.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: One hundred thirty eight pounds for Phebe.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Hit one forty five yesterday.
{DIALOGUE}: Pull her out.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: Two hundred six pounds for Wiley.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 64.
{META_DATA}: 92 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: How much he pick yesterday?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: Two hundred twenty nine pounds.
{DIALOGUE}: Wiley is pulled from the line, huddled with Solomon.
{META_DATA}: 93
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/YARD - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the distance, a flogging is going on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon, Phebe, and Wiley are stripped, placed in a stockade and now being given a perfunctory whipping delivered by ANOTHER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: IDENTIFIED SLAVE.
{META_DATA}: 94
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Evening, but the day is not yet done.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Slaves attend their various evening chores; feeding livestock, doing laundry, cooking food.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is no respite from a slave's charge.
{META_DATA}: 95
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/SLAVE SHACK - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A fire is kindled in the cabin.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves finally fix their own dinner of corn meal.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Corn is ground in a small hand mill.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The corn meal is mixed with a little water, placed in the fire and baked.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: When it is "done brown" the ashes are scraped off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bacon is fried.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the slaves eat, Abram goes on in great length and with much emotion about General Jackson.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE ABRAM
{DIALOGUE}: Hold my words: General Jackson will forever be immortalized.
{DIALOGUE}: His bravery will be handed down to the last posterity.
{DIALOGUE}: If ever there be a stain upon "raw militia," he done wiped away on the eight of January.
{DIALOGUE}: I say da result a that day's battle is of 'mo importance to our grand nation than any occurrence 'fo or since.
{DIALOGUE}: Great man.
{DIALOGUE}: Great man in deed.
{DIALOGUE}: We all need pray to Heavenly Father da General reign over us always.
{META_DATA}: 96
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/SLAVE SHACK - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves are sleeping.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is a loud commotion.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Epps enters, drunkenly, forcing the slaves awake.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 65.
{META_DATA}: 96 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Get up!
{DIALOGUE}: Get up, we dance tonight!
{DIALOGUE}: We will not waste the evenin' with yer laziness.
{DIALOGUE}: Get up.
{META_DATA}: 97
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/MAIN HOUSE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Despite the lateness of the hour, the slaves are up and now fully dressed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They take up position in the middle of the floor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They wait, poised like actors.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon strikes up a tune; Henry joins in with a pan flute and the slaves dance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They do so very wearily.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The whole of it certainly more torture than pleasure.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Epps, whip in hand:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Where's yah merriment?
{DIALOGUE}: Move yer feet.
{DIALOGUE}: As the slaves twirl about Epps keeps an attentive eye on Patsey.
{DIALOGUE}: It should be quite clear that his primary motivation for holding dances is so that he may view Patsey twirl about the floor.
{DIALOGUE}: This fact is not lost on Mistress Epps.
{DIALOGUE}: A few moments of Epps's lust on display is all that the Mistress can bear.
{DIALOGUE}: Jealousy mounting, she snatches up a CARAFE.
{DIALOGUE}: With all her might she throws it at Patsey.
{DIALOGUE}: It hits Patsey square in the face.
{DIALOGUE}: TOO THICK TO SHATTER, IT LEAVES HER BLOODY AND WRITHING ON THE FLOOR.
{DIALOGUE}: The dancing, the music stop.
{DIALOGUE}: The slaves, however, react as though it is not the first time they've seen as much from the Mistress.
{DIALOGUE}: Mistress Epps, screaming like a hellion:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Sell her!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: C'mon, now.
{DIALOGUE}: Wha's this?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: You will sell the negress!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: You're talkin' foolish.
{DIALOGUE}: Sell little Pats?
{DIALOGUE}: She pick with more vigor than any other nigger!
{DIALOGUE}: Choose another ta go.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: No other.
{DIALOGUE}: Sell her!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: I will not!
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 66.
{META_DATA}: 97 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: You will remove that black bitch from this property, 'er I'll take myself back to Cheneyville.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Back to that hog's trough where I found you?
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, the idleness of that yarn washes over me.
{DIALOGUE}: Do not set yourself up against Patsey, my dear.
{DIALOGUE}: That's a wager on which you will not profit.
{DIALOGUE}: Calm yerself.
{DIALOGUE}: And settle for my affection, 'cause my affection you got.
{DIALOGUE}: Or, go.
{DIALOGUE}: 'Cause I will rid myself of yah well before I do away with her!
{DIALOGUE}: Mistress Epps stands irate, lost in fury and unable to even think of what to do.
{DIALOGUE}: Eventually, optionless, she storms away.
{DIALOGUE}: For a few beats there is only the sound of Patsey sobbing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: That damned woman!
{DIALOGUE}: I won't have my mood spoiled.
{DIALOGUE}: I will not.
{DIALOGUE}: Dance!
{DIALOGUE}: Epps sends the whip in Solomon's direction.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon responds by playing.
{DIALOGUE}: Treach literally drags the prone Patsey from the floor, blood still spilling from her face.
{DIALOGUE}: The slaves, as ordered, return to dancing.
{META_DATA}: 98
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -AUGUST, 1843- The sun has only just risen above the horizon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FROM THE GREAT HOUSE THE HORN IS BLOWN signaling the start of another day.
{META_DATA}: 99
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/FIELD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Slaves are in the field picking cotton.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They accompany their work with a SPIRITUAL.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 100 EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/GREAT HOUSE - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the slaves make their way in from the field, the Mistress calls to Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SHE HAS A PIECE OF PAPER IN
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: HAND.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 67.
{META_DATA}: 100 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Platt...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, Mistress.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Can you find your way to Bartholomew's?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I can, ma'am.
{DIALOGUE}: Handing Solomon a sheet of paper.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: This is a list of goods and sundries.
{DIALOGUE}: You will take it to be filled and return immediately.
{DIALOGUE}: Tell Bartholomew to add it to our debt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I will, Mistress.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon looks at the list.
{DIALOGUE}: In a careless moment, Solomon reads quietly from it.
{DIALOGUE}: He catches himself, but not before the Mistress notes his action.
{DIALOGUE}: With high
{META_DATA}: INQUISITIVENESS:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Where yah from, Platt?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I have told you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Tell me again.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Washington.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Who were yah Master?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Master name of Freeman.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Was he a learned man?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I suppose so.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: He learn yah ta read?
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 68.
{META_DATA}: 100 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: A word here or there, but I have no understanding of the written text.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Don't trouble yer self with it.
{DIALOGUE}: Same as the rest, Master bought yah to work.
{DIALOGUE}: Tha's all.
{DIALOGUE}: And any more'll earn yah a hun'red lashes.
{DIALOGUE}: Having delivered her cool advice, Mistress heads back into the house.
{META_DATA}: A101
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon walks along a well-worn path, shopping bag draped over one shoulder.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see his feet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the walk slowly gathers pace, Solomon suddenly turns left into dense foliage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His tread is now a full blown sprint, trees flash past as Solomon attacks his way through the woods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sound of branches cracking underneath.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His feet, heartbeat and breath almost deafening.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is desperate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The violence of his advance abruptly stops, there is silence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see in a clearance a posse of patrollers, preparing for a lynching of two young men.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon's eyes meet theirs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The two men look back at Solomon with a look of fear as one of the patrollers checks the noose around their neck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly the bloodhounds start barking and the patrollers turn in the direction of Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon's whole body shakes with anticipation.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATROLLER
{META_DATA}: (AGGRESSIVELY)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Boy, where are you going?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{META_DATA}: (almost tripping over
{CHARACTER_NAME}: HIS WORDS)
{DIALOGUE}: To the store, Sir, to Bartholomew's.
{DIALOGUE}: I was sent there by Mistress Epps.
{DIALOGUE}: The patroller reaches out for Solomon's free pass around his neck, yanking him forward.
{DIALOGUE}: He looks at it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATROLLER
{DIALOGUE}: Get there and get there quick.
{DIALOGUE}: The patroller kicks Solomon hard, sending him on his way.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon walks on, looking one more time at the two young men; again there is a moment of connection.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon turns.
{DIALOGUE}: The two men are hoisted up, kicking and spitting, behind his shoulder.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon finds himself back on the trail walking towards Bartholomew's, his face now full of shock and
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 68A.
{META_DATA}: A101 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: trepidation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He walks, fighting to calm himself down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We move behind him as he continues his journey, a lonely figure.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 101 INT. BARTHOLOMEW'S - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A general store in the township of Holmesville.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon stands at the counter as BARTHOLOMEW fills Mistress Epps's order.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Among the items set before Solomon is a
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: QUANTITY OF FOOLSCAP.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The items are collected for Solomon and placed in a sack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon giving little thought to them other than getting them back to the mistress.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he turns, he glimpses the regalia of slave restraints, of all different guises; chains, muzzles for sale.
{META_DATA}: 102
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/GREAT HOUSE - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon returns and delivers the items to the Mistress.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Any trouble?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: No, ma'am.
{DIALOGUE}: No trouble.
{META_DATA}: 103
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OMIT - MOVED TO A105
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 104 EXT. SHAW'S HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -JULY, 1844- Sitting on the Grand house's Piazza, Patsey is having tea with MISTRESS HARRIET SHAW, WHO IS A BLACK WOMAN.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Though once a slave, she is now comparatively refined though not wholly so.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The table where they sit is adorned with white linens, and they are attended by a HOUSE NIGGER.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It makes for a tranquil surreal scene.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MASTER SHAW, A WHITE MAN, IS ON THE LAWN GROOMING A
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: HORSE.
{META_DATA}: 69.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: A105 EXT. ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon is running flat out along the road.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Running as though his life depended on getting to his destination in beyond a timely manner.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: B105 EXT. SHAW'S HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still running, slick with sweat, Solomon comes upon the
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SHAW HOUSE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Solomon arrives:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MASTER SHAW
{DIALOGUE}: Platt Epps, good Sunday morning.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Good morning, Master Shaw.
{DIALOGUE}: I've been sent by Master to retrieve Patsey.
{DIALOGUE}: May I approach?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MASTER SHAW
{DIALOGUE}: You may.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon makes his way over to the piazza.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Excuse me, Mistress Shaw.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS SHAW
{DIALOGUE}: Nigger Platt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: My apologies.
{DIALOGUE}: Patsey, Master wishes you to return.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: Sabbath day.
{DIALOGUE}: I's free ta roam.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Understood.
{DIALOGUE}: But the Master sent me running to fetch you, and said no time should be wasted.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS SHAW
{DIALOGUE}: Drink tea?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you, Mistress, but I don't dare.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS SHAW
{DIALOGUE}: Would you knowed Massa Epps's consternation ta be any lessened wit your timely return?
{DIALOGUE}: Sit.
{DIALOGUE}: Sit and drink the tea that offered.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 70.
{META_DATA}: B105 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon knows better, but he sits and the Mistress has tea poured for him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS SHAW (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: What'n was Epps's concern?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: ...I'd rather not say...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS SHAW
{DIALOGUE}: L'il gossip on the Sabbath be fine.
{DIALOGUE}: All things in moderation.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon is not sure what to say.
{DIALOGUE}: He struggles to be as diplomatic as possible.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: As you are aware, Master Epps can be a man of a hard countenance.
{DIALOGUE}: There are times when it is impossible to account for his logic.
{DIALOGUE}: You know he has ill feelings toward your husband.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS SHAW
{DIALOGUE}: He do.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Master Epps has somehow come to believe, as incorrectly as it may be, that Master Shaw is... That he is something of a lothario and an unprincipled man.
{DIALOGUE}: A misguided belief born out of their mutual competition as planters, no doubt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS SHAW
{DIALOGUE}: No doubt...if not born outta truth itself.
{DIALOGUE}: The Mistress waves to Shaw.
{DIALOGUE}: Shaw, unsuspecting of the conversation, waves back.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I'm certain Patsey's well being is Master Epps's only concern.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS SHAW
{DIALOGUE}: Nothin' Epps desire come outta concern.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I meant no disrespect.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS SHAW
{DIALOGUE}: He ain't heard you.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 71.
{META_DATA}: B105 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I meant no disrespect to you, Mistress.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS SHAW
{DIALOGUE}: Ha!
{DIALOGUE}: You worry for me?
{DIALOGUE}: Got no cause to worry for my sensibilities.
{DIALOGUE}: I ain't felt the end of a lash in 'mo years than I cain recall.
{DIALOGUE}: Ain't worked a field, neither.
{DIALOGUE}: Where one time I served, now I got others servin' me.
{DIALOGUE}: The cost to my current existence be Massa Shaw broadcasting his affections, 'n me enjoyin' his pantomime of fidelity.
{DIALOGUE}: If that what keep me from the cotton pickin' niggers, that what it be.
{DIALOGUE}: A small and reasonable price to be paid 'fo sure.
{DIALOGUE}: Looking toward Patsey, speaking with great empathy:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS SHAW (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I knowed what it like to be the object of Massa's predilections and peculiarities.
{DIALOGUE}: And I knowed they can get expressed with kindness or wit violence.
{DIALOGUE}: A lusty visit in the night, or a visitation from the whip.
{DIALOGUE}: And wit my experience, if'n I can give comfort, then comfort I give.
{DIALOGUE}: And you take comfort, Patsey; the Good Lord will manage Epps.
{DIALOGUE}: In His own time the Good Lord will manage dem all.
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, Lordy, there's a day comin' that will burn as an oven.
{DIALOGUE}: It comin' as sure as the Lord is just.
{DIALOGUE}: When His will be done...the curse on the Pharos is a poor example of all that wait 'fo the plantation class.
{DIALOGUE}: Mistress Shaw turns her head to the side, catching a slave's attention.
{DIALOGUE}: As she does so, the slave, a YOUNG WOMAN, commences to pour tea.
{DIALOGUE}: As if to punctuate her thought, the Mistress takes a sip of her tea.
{META_DATA}: 105
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. EPPS'S PLANTATION - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon and Patsey are returning from Shaw's.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Waiting on the porch of the Great House, a drunk Epps beckons for Patsey, his lewd intentions obvious.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 72.
{META_DATA}: 105 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Pats...!
{DIALOGUE}: Patsey!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Do not look in his direction.
{DIALOGUE}: Continue on.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps does not care to be ignored.
{DIALOGUE}: He lifts himself and moves toward the pair in a rage.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Patsey...!
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon moves between Epps and Patsey, cutting Epps off as Patsey continues on.
{DIALOGUE}: Playing up his "ignorance" of
{META_DATA}: THE SITUATION:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Found her, Master, and brought her back just as instructed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: What'd you jus now tell her?
{DIALOGUE}: What'd you say to Pats?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: No words were spoken.
{DIALOGUE}: None of consequence.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Lie!
{DIALOGUE}: Damned liar!
{DIALOGUE}: Saw you talkin' with 'er.
{DIALOGUE}: Tell me!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I cannot speak of what did not occur.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps grabs Solomon.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: I'll cut your black throat.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon pulls away from Epps, RIPPING HIS SHIRT IN THE PROCESS.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps gives chase.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon begins to run around the large pig sty, easily keeping his distance.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps, however is undeterred.
{DIALOGUE}: He moves after Solomon as speedily as he can, which isn't very speedily at all.
{DIALOGUE}: And quickly he tires.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps is forced to bend over and suck air.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon maintains his distance, barely breathing hard.
{DIALOGUE}: His breath returned to him, Epps starts up the chase again.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon runs on out of reach.
{DIALOGUE}: Shortly, Epps again stops, gets his breath... And now in what should be quite comical, Epps again runs after Solomon.
{DIALOGUE}: Again, Epps's vigor leaves him before he can even get close to the slave.
{DIALOGUE}: Dropping down to the dirt, in a show of regret and piety:
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 73.
{META_DATA}: 105 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Platt... Platt, liquor filled me.
{DIALOGUE}: I admit that it did, and I done over reacted.
{DIALOGUE}: It's the Lord's day.
{DIALOGUE}: Ain't nothin' Christian in us carryin' on like this.
{DIALOGUE}: Help me ta my feet, and let us both pray to the Lord for forgiveness.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps extends a hand to Solomon.
{DIALOGUE}: Cautiously, Solomon moves close, but not too close.
{DIALOGUE}: As Solomon draws within striking distance, Epps lunges for him.
{DIALOGUE}: He chases Solomon on until he is again out of breath and once more drops down.
{DIALOGUE}: And again offering a treaty:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm all done in, Platt.
{DIALOGUE}: I have met my limitations, and I ain't equal to 'em.
{DIALOGUE}: I concede to yah, but in the name of valor, help yer master to his feet.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon cautiously moves closer to help.
{DIALOGUE}: Again he is attacked by Epps - this time by knife.
{DIALOGUE}: Sort of.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps is too drunk and tired to fully open the folding blade - and chased far around the field by Epps.
{DIALOGUE}: ALL OF THE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PRECEDING SHOULD BE MORE FUNNY THAN SHOCKING.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A CHANGE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OF PACE FROM THE OTHERWISE NECESSARY BLEAKNESS OF SLAVE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: LIFE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mistress Epps comes running from the house to the pair.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: What?
{DIALOGUE}: Wha's the fuss?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: A misunderstanding is all.
{DIALOGUE}: It began when I was sent to retrieve Patsey from where she'd taken sabbatical at Master Shaw's.
{DIALOGUE}: Upon returning, Master Epps believed Patsey and me to be in conversation when we were not.
{DIALOGUE}: I tried to explain, but it lead to all this.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: What is it?
{DIALOGUE}: Ya cain't remain the Sabbath without her under your eye?
{DIALOGUE}: Ya are a no-account bastard.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Hold a moment...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: A filthy, godless heathen.
{DIALOGUE}: My bed is too holy for yah ta share.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 74.
