{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Of yer misbegotten ways.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: And he would know what of anythin'?
{DIALOGUE}: I ain't even spoken with him today.
{DIALOGUE}: Platt, yah lyin' nigger, have I?
{DIALOGUE}: Have I?
{DIALOGUE}: Discretion being the better part and all, Solomon remains silent.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: There; there's all the truth he got.
{DIALOGUE}: Damned nigger.
{DIALOGUE}: Damn yah.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps pushes his way past the Mistress.
{META_DATA}: 106
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/FIELD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -AUGUST, 1844- With the sun yet again high in the sky the slaves are working the field picking cotton.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As before THEY SING A SPIRITUAL, the only thing that distracts them from the tedium at hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But there is no distracting from the heat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Henry begin to falter before it... And eventually collapse right in the dirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Though the other slaves take note, none move to help him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: None dare.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From Treach rather matter of factly:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: Get him water.
{DIALOGUE}: Edward runs to fetch a gourd.
{DIALOGUE}: He carries it to Henry,
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: DUMPS THE WATER ON HIM, BUT DOES NOT ACTUALLY GIVE HENRY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANYTHING TO DRINK.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Roused, Henry rights himself.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EDWARD
{DIALOGUE}: Go'won.
{DIALOGUE}: Git up.
{DIALOGUE}: Unsteadily, Henry lifts himself and goes back to picking cotton.
{DIALOGUE}: He joins in again with the spiritual, as if the song is all that can keep him going.
{META_DATA}: 107
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/SLAVE SHACKS - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -OCTOBER, 1844-
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 75.
{META_DATA}: 107 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves are asleep.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Epps arrives, again without knocking, with his whip in hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves stir.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Uncle
{META_DATA}: ABRAM ASKS:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE ABRAM
{DIALOGUE}: We dance tonight, massa?
{DIALOGUE}: Epps remains quietly focused on Patsey.
{DIALOGUE}: And it's clear from her apprehensive expression just what it is he's come looking for.
{DIALOGUE}: This time there is no escaping it.
{DIALOGUE}: As if to acknowledge the badness to come, Phebe lightly cries.
{META_DATA}: 108
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/SMOKE HOUSE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On top of a wood pile, in the back of the smoke house - Epps shoves Patsey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stops, stands as if gathering his manhood, then he's all over Patsey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is rough and clumsy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It looks like something between an awkward rape and a virgin attempting his first sexual encounter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Patsey does not respond in any way other than to continually turn her head from Epps, but otherwise remain as still as possible.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: If there is such a thing, she is vicious with her passive aggressiveness.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Epps's frustration mounts until - as the Mistress Shaw had cautioned - he crosses the line from passion to violence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He begins slapping Patsey to get a response from her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: When that fails, he punches her which only leads to him taking up his whip and lashing Patsey MERCILESSLY.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Still, she gives him nothing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Beaten, Patsey sits in the dirt among the cotton, Epps deep breathing above her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The desire for sex now having left him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Epps heads from the field.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Patsey is left where she is.
{META_DATA}: 109
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BARTHOLOMEW'S - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -NOVEMBER, 1844- As before, Solomon waits as Bartholomew fills Mistress Epps order.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Among the items set before Solomon is another quantity of foolscap.
{META_DATA}: 110
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon is making his way back to the Epps plantation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He carries with him a sack filled with the goods from the store.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he walks, SOLOMON LOOKS AROUND CASUALLY.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: When he is certain he is alone, he sets down the sack, opens it and appropriates A SINGLE SHEET OF THE PAPER which he folds and places in his pocket.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: That done, he cinches up the sack and continues on his way.
{META_DATA}: 76.
{META_DATA}: 111 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 112 INT. EPPS'S PLANTATION/SLAVE SHACK - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon takes the slip of paper and hides it within his fiddle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Perhaps the safest place he can think of.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He acts as though he's hiding away found gold.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In reality it's more than that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For Solomon the paper is a first step toward freedom.
{META_DATA}: 113
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/MAIN HOUSE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -DECEMBER, 1844- It's another night of Epps's forced revelry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coming in quick from the previous scene, we go from Solomon holding his fiddle, to playing it as the slaves are again made to dance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mistress Epps brings out a tray of freshly baked pastries.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She sets them down on a table.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: A moment from the dancing.
{DIALOGUE}: Come sample what I baked for y'all.
{DIALOGUE}: The slaves, thankful for the rest as much as the food, file toward the tray reciting a chorus of "Thank you, Mistress."
{DIALOGUE}: As Patsey moves toward the pastries:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: There'll be none for you, Patsey.
{DIALOGUE}: Patsey merely turns away.
{DIALOGUE}: Her non responsiveness, however, serves only to incite the Mistress.
{DIALOGUE}: Screaming:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Yah see that?
{DIALOGUE}: Did yah see the look of insolence she give me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Seen nothin' but her turn away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Are you blind or ignorant?
{DIALOGUE}: It was hot, hateful scorn.
{DIALOGUE}: It filled that black face.
{DIALOGUE}: Yah tell me yah did'n see it, then yah choose not to look, or yah sayin' I lie.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Whatever it was, it passed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Is that how yah are with the niggers?
{DIALOGUE}: Let every ill thought fester inside 'em.
{DIALOGUE}: Look at 'em.
{META_DATA}: (MORE) (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 77.
{META_DATA}: 113 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: They foul with it; foul with their hate.
{DIALOGUE}: You let it be, it'll come back to us in the dark a night.
{DIALOGUE}: Yah want that?
{DIALOGUE}: Yah want them black animals to leave us gut like pigs in our own sleep?
{DIALOGUE}: Epps isn't sure how to respond to the inchoate berating.
{DIALOGUE}: It's an invitation for the Mistress to continue.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: You are manless.
{DIALOGUE}: A damned eunuch if ever there was.
{DIALOGUE}: And if yah won't stand for me, I'd pray you'd at least be a credit to yer own kind and beat every foul thought from 'em.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps does nothing.
{DIALOGUE}: The Mistress lets her anger loose.
{DIALOGUE}: She moves quickly to Patsey, DRIVES HER NAILS INTO THE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PATSEY'S FACE AND DRAWS THEM DOWN ACROSS HER FEATURES.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FIVE DEEP AND BLOODY GASHES ARE LEFT IN PATSEY'S SKIN, the moment marked with appropriate screams.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Patsey collapses on the floor, covering her bleeding face.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Beat it from 'em!
{DIALOGUE}: Thoroughly cuckolded by the Mistress's actions, Epps takes his whip and pulls Patsey out of the house.
{DIALOGUE}: His intentions are plain.
{DIALOGUE}: All the slaves remain silent.
{DIALOGUE}: The Mistress, however, displaying high satisfaction, entreats the others:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Eat.
{DIALOGUE}: Fill yourselves.
{DIALOGUE}: ...And then we dance.
{DIALOGUE}: The slaves eat, but without a hint of levity.
{META_DATA}: 114
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/SLAVE SHACK - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We come up on the slaves who lay sleeping.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All except for Patsey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She rises from her bedding, goes to a corner of the cabin and removes something from a secretive location.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She then moves over to Platt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: Platt... Platt, you awake?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I am.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: I have a request; an act of kindness.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 78.
{META_DATA}: 114 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Patsey displays what she took from hiding.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is a
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: LADY'S FINGER RING.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I secreted it from the Mistress.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Return it!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: It yours, Platt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: For what cause?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: All I ask: end my life.
{DIALOGUE}: Take my body to the margin of the swamp-- Solomon looks at Patsey as though she were insane.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: Take me by the throat.
{DIALOGUE}: Hold me low in the water until I's still 'n without life.
{DIALOGUE}: Bury me in a lonely place of dyin'.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: No!
{DIALOGUE}: I will do no such thing.
{DIALOGUE}: The...the gory detail with which
{META_DATA}: YOU SPEAK--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: I thought on it long and hard.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: It is melancholia, nothing more.
{DIALOGUE}: How does such despair even come to you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: How can you not know?
{DIALOGUE}: I got no comfort in this life.
{DIALOGUE}: If I cain't buy mercy from yah, I'll beg it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: There are others.
{DIALOGUE}: Beg them.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: I'm begging you!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Why?
{DIALOGUE}: Why would you consign me to damnation with such an un-Godly request?
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 79.
{META_DATA}: 114 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: There is God here!
{DIALOGUE}: God is merciful, and He forgive merciful acts.
{DIALOGUE}: Won't be no hell for you.
{DIALOGUE}: Do it.
{DIALOGUE}: Do what I ain't got the strength ta do myself.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon says nothing.
{DIALOGUE}: Clearly he's not about to do the deed.
{DIALOGUE}: With nothing else to do, knowing she is damned with every breath she draws, Patsey crawls back to her spot on the floor and lays herself down.
{META_DATA}: BLACK
{META_DATA}: 115
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/FIELD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -JULY, 1846- Hard times on the planation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Where previously the field in bloom was a carpet of white, it is now patchy and under grown.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves move through the field picking not cotton, but rather COTTON WORMS from the plants.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The cotton worms have dined on the cotton and nearly destroyed the crop.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see the cotton worms in extreme close-up, moving among and destroying the cotton crop.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Epps is beside himself as he looks out over his ruined field.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: It is a plague.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: Cotton worm.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: A plague!
{DIALOGUE}: It's damn Biblical.
{DIALOGUE}: Two season God done sent a plague to smite me.
{DIALOGUE}: I am near ruination.
{DIALOGUE}: Why, Treach?
{DIALOGUE}: What I done that God hate me so?
{DIALOGUE}: Do I not preach His word?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: The whole Bayou sufferin'.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: I don't care nothin' fer the damn Bayou.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sufferin'.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps looks among his slaves at work, his enmity growing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: It's that Godless lot.
{DIALOGUE}: They brought this on me.
{DIALOGUE}: I bring 'em
{META_DATA}: (MORE) (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 80.
{META_DATA}: 115 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: God's word, and heathens they are, they brung me God's scorn.
{DIALOGUE}: Crazed, Epps runs into the field, taking himself from slave to slave delivering a whipping to all he can lay his hands on.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Damn you!
{DIALOGUE}: Damn you all!
{DIALOGUE}: Damn you!
{META_DATA}: 116
{META_DATA}: RE-OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 117 EXT. JUDGE TURNER'S PLANTATION - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -OCTOBER, 1846- Henry, Bob, Uncle Abram and Solomon sit in the back of a cart.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SOLOMON HAS HIS FIDDLE WITH HIM.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Epps has delivered the men to JUDGE TURNER, a distinguished man and extensive planter whose large estate is situated on Bayou Salle within a few miles of the gulf.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Epps and Turner stand off to one side engaged in bargaining as Henry, Bob, Uncle Abram and Solomon wait and watch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One of the slaves whisper under their breath.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS' SLAVE
{DIALOGUE}: I hear cutting cane is twice as hard as picking cotton.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BOB
{DIALOGUE}: But at least we'll be away from Master Epps.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE ABRAM
{DIALOGUE}: Boy, you two have no sense.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps returns to his slaves and gives a parting salutation.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Yer Judge Turner's for the season.
{DIALOGUE}: More if need be, until my crop return.
{DIALOGUE}: Yah'll bring no disrespect to me, and yah'll bring no biblical plagues to him.
{DIALOGUE}: Be decent, ere mark my words, I will deliver an ungodly whippin'.
{META_DATA}: 118
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SLAVE SHACK - NIGHT
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 81.
{META_DATA}: 118 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Slaves are crammed into the shack - LITERALLY ON TOP OF EACH OTHER - as they try to sleep.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Some lay, some sit up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Packed in like cattle, there is barely room to move let alone draw a deep, clean breath.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is a real risk of suffocating in the mass.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Some cough and wheeze.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A CHILD CRIES... Among them is Solomon who must believe at this point that his life has reached its very lowest point.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The odds of survival are slight, let alone the chance of actually ever returning to his family.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This clearly weighs on him as he struggles to find anything like comfortable space in the pen.
{META_DATA}: 119
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. CANE FIELDS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An OVERSEER is explaining to the new slaves - SOLOMON AMONG THEM - how to cultivate cane.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WITH A KNIFE IN HAND he demonstrates the process:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OVERSEER
{DIALOGUE}: Draw the cane from the rick, cut the top and flags from the stalk, understand?
{DIALOGUE}: Leave only that part which is sound and healthy.
{DIALOGUE}: Cast off the rest...
{META_DATA}: 120
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. CANE FIELDS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -NOVEMBER, 1846- ABOUT THIRTY SLAVES are working the field.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are divided into THREE GANGS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The first which draw the cane, the next lay the cane in the drill, the last then hoe the rows after.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon is among a gang that draws and cuts, and he moves with speed and skill.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Certainly more so than he displayed picking cotton.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Standing with his overseer, Judge Turner watches.
{META_DATA}: 121
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SLAVE SHACK - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Again, the slaves have been herded into the shack and pressed together.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he tries to rest - sleep is nearly impossible - Solomon finds himself face to face with a woman, ANNA.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is awake.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For a few beats she avoids eye contact with Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She seems, like Solomon, to be unaccustomed to her surroundings and horribly frightened by them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eventually her eyes meet Solomon's.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She makes no sound, but great apprehension spills from her eyes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Whatever's next, whatever horror awaits, she can barely stand to face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Fear, proximity... They drive her hand
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 81A.
{META_DATA}: 121 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: to Solomon's.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: After a moment of seemingly reacquainting herself with genuine human contact, the woman TAKES
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 82.
{META_DATA}: 121 CONTINUED: (2)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SOLOMON'S HAND AND PRESSES IT TO HER BREAST.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon tries to jerk his hand away, but ANNA HOLDS IT IN PLACE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Manipulating Solomon's hand, she begins to massage her breast.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon takes no real pleasure in the act - really, neither does Anna.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THERE SHOULD BE A TRUE SENSE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANNA IS JUST SO VERY, VERY DESPERATE FOR HUMAN CONTACT,
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FOR THE NEED TO FEEL ALIVE AND LIKE A PERSON RATHER THAN
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: AN ANIMAL THAT EMOTIONALLY SHE IS WILLING TO ENGAGE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SOLOMON.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The need quickly compounds.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anna presses her lips to Solomon's.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Eventually, SHE DIRECTS HIS HAND BENEATH HER DRESS AND BETWEEN HER LEGS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon, with slightly more compassion than a guy making union wages, BEGINS TO MANIPULATE ANNA WITH HIS HAND.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The act remains more perfunctory than passionate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We can see Anna moving toward climax and eventual release.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But more - or substantially less - than joyous sex, it is really just a drug-like inoculation against reality.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But the feeling quickly fades.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All that remains, as with most chance encounters, is regret.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And there is shame, too.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is put on display as Anna turns away from Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As quickly as it began, it is as though the act had not happened at all.
{META_DATA}: 122
{META_DATA}: OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 123 EXT. JUDGE TURNER'S PLANTATION/GREAT HOUSE - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon waits outside the house on the porch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A house servant - ZACHARY - approaches and admonishes Solomon.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ZACHARY
{DIALOGUE}: Off the porch.
{DIALOGUE}: Get off.
{DIALOGUE}: Like a dog shooed away, Solomon steps down.
{DIALOGUE}: Eventually Judge Turner exits the house and crosses to Solomon.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: ...Sir...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JUDGE TURNER
{DIALOGUE}: Platt is it?
{DIALOGUE}: Have you cultivated cane previously?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: No, sir, I have not.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JUDGE TURNER
{DIALOGUE}: You take to it quite naturally.
{DIALOGUE}: Are you educated?
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 83.
{META_DATA}: 123 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Niggers are hired to work, not to read and write.
{DIALOGUE}: Turner gives that a bit of consideration as he gives Solomon a wary looking over.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JUDGE TURNER
{DIALOGUE}: You play the fiddle?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I do.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JUDGE TURNER
{DIALOGUE}: Willard Yarney, a planter up the bayou, celebrates his anniversary in a three week's time.
{DIALOGUE}: I will hold out your name to him.
{DIALOGUE}: What you earn is yours to keep.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JUDGE TURNER
{DIALOGUE}: Mind yourself, Platt.
{META_DATA}: SOLOMON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Yes, sir.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 124 EXT. TURNER PLANTATION - LATER (MOVED FROM 124)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Work over, the slaves congregate to eat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Solomon eats, he takes note of the JUICE FROM SOME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BERRIES ON HIS PLATE.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 125 EXT. TURNER'S PLANTATION - EVENING (MOVED FROM 125)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon plays with a piece of cane, fashions it into some kind of writing tool, testing it in the mud.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He then brushes over the dirt with his hand.
{META_DATA}: 84.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 126 EXT. TURNER PLANTATION - NIGHT (MOVED FROM 126)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Secreted away out near the edge of the bayou and sitting by a small fire, Solomon takes the slip of paper from his fiddle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is yellowed, showing age, but still usable.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dipping the piece of cane - a quill - into the crushed berries, Solomon attempts to write a bit on the paper.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The berry juice, too free-flowing, is unusable as ink.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon returns the paper to the fiddle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has some scraps of food with him, which he snacks on.
{META_DATA}: A127
{META_DATA}: OMITTED
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: A127A INT. SLAVE SHACK - DAY A127A
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see a sharp object scratching onto a surface.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The tool moves on to form another mark.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sound is repetitive and almost unbearable.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As we move out, we see the names Anne, Margaret, Alonzo.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are engraved onto the violin, in the hidden area where Solomon would rest his chin.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon looks at it for a moment, moving his fingertips across the engraving.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His face full of loss.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sadly, he lifts his instrument under his chin and leaning his head to the side as if to play.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 127 INT. YARNEY'S HOUSE - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A party has commenced at the noble home of one MR. YARNEY.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A group of REVELERS have gathered and are on the dance floor, in fancy dress.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their faces are covered with a variation of decorative masks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The party is a feast of celebration.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As entertainment, SOLOMON ACCOMPANIES A GROUP OF MUSICIANS, no more than three.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And as he does so, they all play with jovial liveliness.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Clearly a good time is being had by all.
{META_DATA}: 128
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. ROAD - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His playing done for the evening, Solomon is returning to Judge Turner's on foot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is only the moonlight with which to light the way.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he walks, Solomon eats from a HEARTY CHUCK OF BREAD.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Obviously part of his haul from the evening.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon again hears noises coming from the brush just up ahead of him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon tears off some of the bread, kneels and holds it out before him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: C'mere.
{DIALOGUE}: C'mon, boy.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 85.
{META_DATA}: 128 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This time, there is no dog.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Instead, from the dark and the brush step TWO BLACK MEN.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon stands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks the men over - their clothes tatters and they themselves covered in dirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It becomes quite clear they are not just slaves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A fact confirmed when they step menacingly toward Solomon, ONE WITH A SHIV IN HAND.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At first it seems they want Solomon's food or money.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Worse, THEY GO FOR HIS FIDDLE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon has but a moment to brace himself before he is attacked, TAKING A CUT TO THE ARM.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon fights back, PICKING UP A PINE KNOT and striking his attacker over the head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: That takes the fight out of him, and both men retreat back the way they came leaving Solomon be.
{META_DATA}: A129
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TURNER PLANTATION - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Outside of the slave shacks Solomon's wound tended by Uncle Abram.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he works on it:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE ABRAM
{DIALOGUE}: Runaways I would expect.
{DIALOGUE}: The Bayou full with 'em.
{DIALOGUE}: They nothin' 'mo dangerous than a nigger in flight.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: They acted out of desperation.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE ABRAM
{DIALOGUE}: Act outta lunacy.
{DIALOGUE}: Heads fulla stories 'bout life up north.
{DIALOGUE}: Yah ever been north, Platt?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: ...No...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE ABRAM
{DIALOGUE}: And never should yah be.
{DIALOGUE}: I hope that yah never bear witness the sorry condition of the northern black.
{DIALOGUE}: Got neither no purpose, nor direction.
{DIALOGUE}: They jus...they jus fall about the streets in search of sustenance of both body and spirit.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: You know this to be so?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: UNCLE ABRAM
{DIALOGUE}: Two of my massas tolt me.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 86.
{META_DATA}: A129 CONTINUED:
{META_DATA}: 129 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 130 EXT. TURNER PLANTATION - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -FEBRUARY/MARCH, 1847- Alone out on the edge of the Bayou, Solomon is playing a low air on his violin WHILE SNACKING ON SCRAPS OF BACON.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he plays, something appears in the distance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From the edge of the bayou, coming forth like an apparition arisen from the earth, is CELESTE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is a young woman of about 19 years of age and far whiter than most blacks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: "IT REQUIRED CLOSE INSPECTION TO DISTINGUISH IN HER FEATURE THE SLIGHTEST TRACE OF AFRICAN BLOOD."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Beyond that, she is pale and haggard, but still lovely.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dressed in a white gown, she emerges from the water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Draped on her dress, her period.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A line in her skirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's very visible, but not shocking.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A ribbon of red in her dress.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Celeste moves to Solomon without fear or hesitation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Solomon, startled, takes her in, Celeste says quite
{META_DATA}: PLAINLY:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: I am hungry.
{DIALOGUE}: Give me food.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Who are you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm hungry.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon gives Celeste some of his food.
{DIALOGUE}: Celeste, famished, devours it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: What is your name?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: My name is Celeste.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: What are your circumstances?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: I belong ta Massa Carey, and 'ave been two days among da palmettoes.
{DIALOGUE}: Celeste is sick and cain't work, and would rather die in the swamp
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 87.
{META_DATA}: 130 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: than be whipped to death by the overseer.
{DIALOGUE}: So I took myself away.
{DIALOGUE}: Massa's dogs won't follow me.
{DIALOGUE}: The patrollers 'ave tried to set dem on me.
{DIALOGUE}: But dey a secret between dem and Celeste, and dey won't mind the devilish orders of the overseer.
{DIALOGUE}: Celeste lifts her head from the food on which she gnaws.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Do you believe me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: Why?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: There are some whose tracks the hounds will refuse to follow.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: Give me more food.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm starvin'.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: This is all my allowance for the
{META_DATA}: REST OF--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: Give it to me.
{DIALOGUE}: Almost as if compelled, Solomon does as ordered.
{DIALOGUE}: As she eats, Celeste aggrandizes herself:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Most slaves escape at night.
{DIALOGUE}: The overseers are alert for such chicanes.
{DIALOGUE}: But Celeste tricked dem 'n alight in the middle of the day wit the sun up at its highest.
{DIALOGUE}: The place of my concealment now deep in the swamp, not half a mile from Massa's plantation, and a world apart.
{DIALOGUE}: A world a tall trees whose long arms make fo' a canopy so dense dey keep away even the beams of the sun.
{DIALOGUE}: It twilight always in Celeste's world, even in the brightest day.
{DIALOGUE}: I will live there, and I will live freely.
{DIALOGUE}: The overseers are a cowardly lot.
{DIALOGUE}: Dey will not go where their dogs show fear and where it always be night.
{DIALOGUE}: Others will join me in the twilight, and we ain't gunna be slaves no 'mo forever.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 88.
{META_DATA}: 130 CONTINUED: (2)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon isn't sure what to say.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Before he can say
{META_DATA}: ANYTHING:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Celeste will come to you again in the night.
{DIALOGUE}: You will have food for her.
{DIALOGUE}: Celeste departs the way she came; as though she were a vision.
{META_DATA}: 131
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. JUDGE TURNER'S PLANTATION/FOOD STORAGE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon stealthfully makes his way into the storage shed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dried and smoked meats are hung, and milled corn is about.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Taking out a handkerchief, Solomon begins to load it with food.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Not too much.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Not so much his thievery will be readily noticed, but he does avail himself.
{META_DATA}: 132
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TURNER PLANTATION - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon plays his violin, but plays it with an anxious nature as he waits.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then, as before, a figure appears in the distance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is Celeste coming out of the night.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She makes her way directly to Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With no greeting, she says:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: I am hungry.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon gives Celeste the handkerchief he's filled.
{DIALOGUE}: She opens it, and begins to devour the food.
{DIALOGUE}: As she eats:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I was rude, and didn't even ask yo name.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Platt.
{META_DATA}: (BEAT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon is my true and free name.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: Was you free?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I was.
{DIALOGUE}: I am.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon exposes his wrist, displays his tattoo as he
{META_DATA}: ANNOUNCES:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I remain free in my heart.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 89.
{META_DATA}: 132 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Giving a laugh as though it's the silliest thing she's
{META_DATA}: HEARD:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: Free heart means nothin if'n yo body gunna die a slave.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I will not.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: How?
{DIALOGUE}: Celeste knows you ain't gunna run.
{DIALOGUE}: Celeste knows it ain't your nature.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I have a plan.
{DIALOGUE}: I have a letter.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: A letter?
{DIALOGUE}: How'll yah mail da letter?
{DIALOGUE}: Who yah trust to post it?
{DIALOGUE}: A nigger that can read and write is a nigger that'll hang.
{DIALOGUE}: There is a pause.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon can't answer this question.
{DIALOGUE}: It is the glaring hole in his plan.
{DIALOGUE}: Having finished eating:
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 90.
{META_DATA}: 132 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Celeste will come again in de night.
{DIALOGUE}: You will bring her 'mo food.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I risk discovery to take more.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: You will bring Celeste 'mo food.
{DIALOGUE}: And with that Celeste again moves back into the darkness.
{META_DATA}: 133
{META_DATA}: OMIT
{META_DATA}: 134 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 135 EXT. TURNER PLANTATION - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon is picking at the bark off a WHITE MAPLE.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 136 EXT. TURNER PLANTATION - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In a tin cup, over a fire, Solomon boils the white maple bark in just a bit of water.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 137 INT. JUDGE TURNER'S PLANTATION/SLAVES CABIN - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As others sleep, by the light of dying coals, Solomon uses the quill to test the boiled bark.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The liquid holds as a form of ink.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is no?t ideal, but it is legible on the page.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Armed with this, Solomon writes his letter.
{META_DATA}: 138
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. TURNER PLANTATION - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon sits with Celeste.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He relates his news to her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I have my letter.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: Yah has your freedom then?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: All that remains is to contrive measures by which the letter can safely be deposited in the post office.
{DIALOGUE}: When Celeste speaks she is quite melancholy.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 91.
{META_DATA}: 138 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: I have resolved to return to my Massa.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon gives an unnerved look.
{DIALOGUE}: This is not good news.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Is it more food you need?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: I live in fear.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: None will come after you in the swamps.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: It ain't the patrollers I scared of... At all seasons the howling of wild animals can be heard at night along the border of the swamps.
{DIALOGUE}: At first their calls were welcomin'.
{DIALOGUE}: Dey too was free, 'n I thought dey greeted me like a sistah.
{DIALOGUE}: Lately, dey cries have turned horrifyin'.
{DIALOGUE}: They mean to kill Celeste.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: The solitude plays tricks.
{DIALOGUE}: It's your impression, nothing more.
{DIALOGUE}: If you go back to your master you could face the same.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: My freedom been nothin' but a daydream.
{DIALOGUE}: So was Celeste's thoughts of slaves conjoinin' in the bayou.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Better the loneliness.
{DIALOGUE}: You have been free most of the summer.
{DIALOGUE}: Return now and your master will make example of you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: It is lonely dwellin' waiting for others who won't never come.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 92.
{META_DATA}: 138 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Go north.
{DIALOGUE}: Make your way by night...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: It'll only be worse if'n Celeste don't go back of her own will.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: You won't be caught.
{DIALOGUE}: The dogs won't track you.
{DIALOGUE}: You are...you are unique.
{DIALOGUE}: Celeste...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: You got alternatives, Solomon.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: To return is to die!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CELESTE
{DIALOGUE}: Celeste got no one to write a letter to.
{DIALOGUE}: As if to punctuate her resolve, without a word more Celeste departs toward the swamp.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon starts on into the swamp after her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Celeste... Celeste!
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon continues after Celeste, wading deeper into the dark night and murky waters.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Celeste, I will guide you north!
{DIALOGUE}: Wait, and I will take you.
{DIALOGUE}: Celeste is too nimble.
{DIALOGUE}: She outpaces Solomon, continues on and disappears into the night.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Let me take you!
{DIALOGUE}: Let me go with you!
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon runs on, then splashes to a stop.
{DIALOGUE}: He stumbles around disoriented, calling into the blackness:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Celeste... Nothing.
{DIALOGUE}: No answer.
{DIALOGUE}: Not a human one.
{DIALOGUE}: There are sounds and echoes - some in the distance, some perhaps moving closer - which, moment by moment, become more and more frightening.
{DIALOGUE}: Soon, Solomon realizes he is in quite literally over his head; the water first chest deep, then neck deep.
{DIALOGUE}: With no way to orient himself, no means to guide him in the dark, Solomon's reserve begins to crumble.
{DIALOGUE}: He thrashes in the water trying to find his way
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 93.
{META_DATA}: 138 CONTINUED: (3)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: back to shore.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: No longer trying to save Celeste, Solomon calls to her - desperately - for assistance.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Celeste!
{DIALOGUE}: Come to me, Celeste!
{DIALOGUE}: In that moment Solomon is quite certain he is nearly done; that he will not find land, nor aid and that this is his final moment.
{DIALOGUE}: His panic should be that tangible.
{DIALOGUE}: It is either force of will, or survival instinct...or maybe just pure luck that carries Solomon on until he reaches first muddy ground, then firm footing.
{DIALOGUE}: Hauling himself onto the swamps edge, Solomon finally collapses in a drenched, worn heap.
{DIALOGUE}: His life spared, but Celeste never to be seen again.
{META_DATA}: BLACK
{META_DATA}: 139
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. EPPS'S PLANTATION - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -MAY/JUNE, 1847- We come up now outside of Master Epps's plantation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Epps stands in the drive.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's in surprisingly good spirits as Solomon, Uncle Abram, Henry and Bob trudge their way wearily toward Epps and his other slaves who are gathered.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The cotton field is in full bloom, the crop fully returned.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: A joyous day.
{DIALOGUE}: A joyous day.
{DIALOGUE}: Dark times is behind us.
{DIALOGUE}: Clean livin' 'n prayer done lifted the plague.
{DIALOGUE}: Indicating to the cotton:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: As thick 'n white as New England snow.
{DIALOGUE}: 'N now my niggers is returned to me.
{META_DATA}: (TO SOLOMON)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Heard Judge Turner gave you favor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Oh, did you beguile him, Platt, with your slick nigger ways?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Well, yah won't stand idle, boy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Not on my land.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Much work to do.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Days of old long since, eh?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Joyous!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Joyous indeed!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Throughout Epps's welcome, Solomon's focus is on Patsey who is lined up with the other slaves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SHE IS NOW MORE HAGGARD THAN WHEN WE LAST SAW HER.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her face and arms display many new scars.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's clear that in the intervening years she has quite literally been a whipping boy for Epps and the Mistress.
{META_DATA}: 94.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 140 EXT. EPPS'S PLANTATION/COTTON FIELD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -JULY, 1847- The slaves are out working on the field.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: White hands appear, picking cotton: ARMSBY.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is wholly unskilled at picking cotton, and he puts little effort into the job.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As we meet him he seems a decent sort if a little short on self-motivation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In anachronistic terminology, he'd be called a "slacker."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He joins in with the slaves, singing a spiritual.
{META_DATA}: 141
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/GIN HOUSE - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Epps said, it is days of long since.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves are back to having their cotton weighed in the Gin House
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Wiley...?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: Two hundred sixty pounds.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Bob?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: Three hundred forty pounds for Bob.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Patsey?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: Five hundred twenty pounds.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Tha's a girl.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't never let me down.
{DIALOGUE}: Platt?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: One hundred sixty pounds.
{DIALOGUE}: Before Treach is even done announcing the weight, Epps has pulled Solomon aside to where Uncle Abram already awaits his fate.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Armsby?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: Sixty four pounds.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps speaks to Armsby sternly, but nothing of the manner in which he would address the slaves.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 95.
{META_DATA}: 141 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: A good days labor would average two hundred pounds.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sure in time y'll develope as a picker, but it takes effort, boy.
{DIALOGUE}: Put some damn effort into it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: To Treach, regarding Solomon and Abram:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Take 'em out.
{DIALOGUE}: Get to whippin'.
{DIALOGUE}: No force is needed.
{DIALOGUE}: The slaves understand the situation.
{DIALOGUE}: They follow Treach out of the Gin house.
{META_DATA}: 142
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. EPPS'S PLANTATION/SLAVE SHACK - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We come in after the punishment has been dealt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Patsey tends to Uncle Abram's back as Armsby applies liniments to Solomon's.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he does, Armsby muses:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY
{DIALOGUE}: It's a tragedy.
{DIALOGUE}: How does such come to pass?
{DIALOGUE}: Working a field and picking cotton like a lowly hand.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm of a damn sight better station.
{DIALOGUE}: And my desires never lacked for a grandiose component, though I will admit they have at times been short on ingenuity.
{DIALOGUE}: But only at times.
{DIALOGUE}: I've worked as an overseer, you know.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I did not, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY
{DIALOGUE}: Not "sir."
{DIALOGUE}: Just Armsby.
{DIALOGUE}: Not owed more than any other in the field.
{DIALOGUE}: I worked plantations from Virginia, down into Alabama.
{DIALOGUE}: I could manage easy a hundred slaves and have done so.
{DIALOGUE}: But to toil in the field?
{DIALOGUE}: Never thought that would come to pass.
{DIALOGUE}: Never.
{DIALOGUE}: But times are desperate.
{DIALOGUE}: Where once I had said "no" to Epps and his merger offerings, I returned cap
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 96.
{META_DATA}: 142 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: in hand.
{DIALOGUE}: ...Look at what I've become.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: How did you arrive at such a place, if I may ask?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY
{DIALOGUE}: Ask.
{DIALOGUE}: It's just conversation.
{DIALOGUE}: From a pocket Armsby produces a flask.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I became a little too dependant on the whisky, a little too undependable on the job.
{DIALOGUE}: Before you say I'm just a sorry drunkard, let me state my case: As reliable employment as overseeing is, it's no easy chore on the spirit.
{DIALOGUE}: I say no man of conscious can take the lash to another human day in, and day out without shredding at his own self.
{DIALOGUE}: Takes him to a place where he either makes excuses within his mind to be unaffected... Or finds some way to trample his guilty sensations.
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I trampled.
{DIALOGUE}: Armsby takes a drink.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: And with frequency.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Where is your place of birth?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY
{DIALOGUE}: Maryland.
{DIALOGUE}: Have you traveled there?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: ...I cannot say that I have.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY
{DIALOGUE}: Fine country.
{DIALOGUE}: More seasonal than the bayou.
{DIALOGUE}: A deal less humid.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Why did you leave it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY
{DIALOGUE}: To make my fortune, of course.
{DIALOGUE}: I gave in to tales of wealth and prosperity that were the lore of the southern states: all that's needed being a patch of land and a few good growing seasons.
{DIALOGUE}: Cotton,
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 97.
{META_DATA}: 142 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: or tobacco.
{DIALOGUE}: And then locating a proper bank in which to store your riches.
{DIALOGUE}: But such profitable outcomes are reserved for the plantation masters.
{DIALOGUE}: It's the lot of the rest of us to serve.
{DIALOGUE}: So I settled on being an overseer, and failed as well at that.
{DIALOGUE}: In the meantime my dreams gave way to reality.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, I want nothing more than to earn a decent wage.
{META_DATA}: (BEAT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And get myself home.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Armsby takes another drink and leans back.
{META_DATA}: 143
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/SLAVE SHACKS - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -AUGUST, 1847- We again hear the sound of the HORN BLOWING signaling the start of the work day for the slave.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 144 EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/FIELD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With the sun yet again high in the sky the slaves are working the field picking cotton.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As before they sing a spiritual, the only thing that distracts them from the tedium at hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But there is no distracting from the heat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Uncle Abram begin to falter and finally drop down to the ground.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Treach calls to Edward:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TREACH
{DIALOGUE}: Get him water.
{DIALOGUE}: Edward runs to fetch water which he carries to Abram and
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: DUMPS ON HIM...BUT ABRAM DOES NOT RISE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: DOES NOT MOVE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At this point, the sounds of the singing from the others tapers off as they realize Abram isn't getting up.
{META_DATA}: 145
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/SLAVE CEMETERY - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We are beyond the main of the plantation, the cotton field in the background.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We are at the slaves' cemetery, a mixture of crude crosses and unsettled ground.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon, Bob and Henry, now much visually older than when we first saw them, are digging a grave in the dirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The uncovered body of Abram lays near.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Having dug down an appropriate distance, the three men take the body and, very unceremoniously, place it into the ground.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Holding
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 98.
{META_DATA}: 145 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: the shovel in his hands, and resting it by his feet, Bob tilts his head down and closes his eyes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The others do the same.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Almost stutteringly, not really knowing what to
{META_DATA}: SAY--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BOB
{DIALOGUE}: I just want to say something about Uncle Abram.
{DIALOGUE}: He was a good man and he always looked out for us since we were little.
{DIALOGUE}: God Bless him.
{DIALOGUE}: God love him.
{DIALOGUE}: And God keep him.
{DIALOGUE}: That done, they begin to cover it with dirt.
{DIALOGUE}: It is all the more of a funeral that Abram will receive.
{META_DATA}: 146
{META_DATA}: OMIT
{META_DATA}: 147 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: A148 EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/SLAVE CEMETERY - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A female voice appears out of the blackness and begins to sing solo, "Went down to the river Jordan."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A response of "Oh Yeah" quickly follows.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Again the singer continues, "where John baptized three."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The same faces we have seen on Epps' plantation, but now filled with rapture, appear.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's as if the voices have created a new form of awakening and presence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It seems to transcend and translate in a strange way, joy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A joy which has un-yet been seen on screen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A joy which has been hidden, but a joy which is undoubtedly there.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's captivating, infectious.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This should be a moving part of the film, which stirs the audience and, for a moment, relieves them of the seemingly chastising environment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The singer continues, "Well some say John was a Baptist, some say John was a Jew, but I say John was a preacher, because the Bible says so too, preach on Johnny."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And with that, the rest of the congregation chant "I believe.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Oh, I believe."
{META_DATA}: 148
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. EPPS'S PLANTATION/WOODS - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon goes to RETRIEVE THE SMALL PACKAGE FROM UNDER A ROCK AT THE BASE OF A TREE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon returns the letter to hiding.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He takes the money with him and cautiously moves from the area.
{META_DATA}: 149
{META_DATA}: OMIT
{META_DATA}: 99.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 150 INT. EPPS'S PLANTATION/ARMSBY'S SHACK - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door opens.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon enters.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Armsby is surprised to see him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: So much so, he isn't sure what greeting to give.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon gives a blunt introduction.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Re: the
{META_DATA}: COINS:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: The proceeds of my fiddling performances.
{DIALOGUE}: A few picayunes, but all I have in the world.
{DIALOGUE}: I promise them to you if you will do me the favor I require.
{DIALOGUE}: But I beg you not to expose me if you cannot grant the request.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY
{DIALOGUE}: What do you ask?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: First, your word, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY
{DIALOGUE}: On my honor.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: It is a simple enough request.
{DIALOGUE}: I ask only that you deposit a letter in the Marksville post office.
{DIALOGUE}: And that you keep the action an inviolable secret forever.
{DIALOGUE}: The details of the letter are of no consequence.
{DIALOGUE}: Even at that, there would be an imposition of much pain and suffering were it known I was the author.
{DIALOGUE}: A patron is what I require, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY
{DIALOGUE}: Where's the letter now?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: ...It is not yet written.
{DIALOGUE}: I will have it in a day.
{DIALOGUE}: Two at most, my skill with composition as poor as it is.
{DIALOGUE}: Armsby considers the request.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY
{DIALOGUE}: I will do it.
{DIALOGUE}: And will accept whatever payment is offered.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon hesitates.
{DIALOGUE}: In the moment, he's not so sure he can wholly give himself over to trust.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 100.
{META_DATA}: 150 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: To assist you, I put my own self at risk.
{DIALOGUE}: I will do so, but fair compensation is all I ask.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon hands over the money.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ARMSBY (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Draw up your letter.
{DIALOGUE}: We will meet again.
{DIALOGUE}: In two days?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: In two days.
{DIALOGUE}: ...Thank you.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon exits.
{META_DATA}: 151
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. EPPS'S PLANTATION/COTTON FIELD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon and the slaves pick cotton.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Armsby is conspicuously NOT laboring in the field.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Solomon works he is watched by Epps.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Watched more than he normally is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For a moment it seems it might just be a matter of perspective; Solomon's unease over his actions.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But soon Epps is joined by Armsby.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The two men stand and talk, their looks locked toward Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Whatever it is that is occurring between them continues for a long, long moment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But Epps makes no move toward Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon continues with his work.
{META_DATA}: 152
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. EPPS'S PLANTATION/SLAVE SHACK - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves are at rest.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Gripping his whip Epps enters, without so much as a knock at the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For a moment there's curiosity; is he there for a dance, for Patsey...?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Looking right to Solomon:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Get up.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon does.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps heads back out into the dark.
{DIALOGUE}: He says nothing, but his directive is clear: Follow me.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 153 EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/SLAVE SHACK - CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon comes out into the dark.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nearly hidden in the shadows is a bitter Epps.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Despite the lack of light, Epps's malevolence is quite clear.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His whip attached to his hip.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he speaks, he stokes himself with swigs from a FLASK.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Epps puts his arm around Solomon, as if consoling a friend, and guides him into the woods.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 100A.
{META_DATA}: 153 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Well, boy.
{DIALOGUE}: I understand I've got a larned nigger that writes
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 101.
{META_DATA}: 153 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: letters and tries to get white fellows to mail 'em.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon, hardly missing a beat, plays this off.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, Armsby tol' me today the devil was among my niggers.
{DIALOGUE}: That I had one that needed close watchin' or he would run away.
{DIALOGUE}: When I axed him why, he said you come over to him and waked him up in the middle of the night and wanted him to carry a letter to Marksville.
{DIALOGUE}: What have yah got to say to that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: All I have to say, master, is all that need be said.
{DIALOGUE}: There is no truth in it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: You say.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: How could I write a letter without ink or paper?
{DIALOGUE}: There is nobody I want to write to 'cause I hain't got no friends living as I know of.
{DIALOGUE}: That Armsby is a lying drunken fellow.
{DIALOGUE}: You know this, just as you know that I am constant in truth.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, master, I can see what that Armsby is after, plain enough.
{DIALOGUE}: Didn't he want you to hire him for an overseer?
{DIALOGUE}: A beat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: That's it.
{DIALOGUE}: He wants to make you believe we're all going to run away and then he thinks you'll hire an overseer to watch us.
{DIALOGUE}: He believes you are soft soap.
{DIALOGUE}: He's given to such talk.
{DIALOGUE}: I believe he's just made this story out of whole cloth, 'cause he wants to get a situation.
{DIALOGUE}: It's all a lie, master, you may depend on't.
{DIALOGUE}: It's all a lie.
{DIALOGUE}: For a tense moment we are unsure which way Epps'll go.
{DIALOGUE}: Increasingly it become apparent that, shallow minded and equally soused, Solomon has been able to fold Epps's thoughts.
{DIALOGUE}: In a low curse that clearly states his ill intentions.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 102.
{META_DATA}: 153 CONTINUED: (3)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Revealed is a pocket knife, which all through the conversation, unknown to us the audience, was pushed up against Solomon's stomach.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Epps speaks, he closes it and taps it on Solomon's shoulder.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: I'm damned.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll be god... Were he not free and white, Platt.
{DIALOGUE}: Were he not free and white.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps heads off.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon is left to exhale a deep breath.
{META_DATA}: 154
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/WOODS - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Having found a lonely spot, Solomon has struck a SMALL FIRE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has in his hand his letter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With no ceremony, he casts the letter upon the flames and watches it burn.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And with it, at this time, seems all chance of him ever being free.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stands and looks at it as if forever, as ashes descend into the night sky.
{META_DATA}: FADE TO BLACK.
{META_DATA}: A155
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/GREAT HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -MARCH, 1852- The slaves are now employed working on an extension to the Great House.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves work under the direction of MR. SAMUEL BASS, a between forty and fifty years old, of light complexion and light hair.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is cool and self- possessed, fond of argument, but always speaking with extreme deliberation as well as a Canadian accent.
{META_DATA}: B155
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/GREAT HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the slaves continue to work, there is a conversation going on between Epps and Bass.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bass much skilled in the art of sophistry, while Epps's arguments are fueled mostly by emotion alone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Though at first Epps does little more than joke his way around the facts.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon, working still, can't help but overhear as Epps offers Bass a drink, which Bass waves away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Take it.
{DIALOGUE}: You look unsettled.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: I'm well.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: No shame in taking respite from the heat; drink, shade.
{DIALOGUE}: It's ungodly for travelers.
{DIALOGUE}: Hearty, or otherwise.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 102A.
{META_DATA}: B155 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bass gives a laugh.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I meant no joke.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 103.
{META_DATA}: B155 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: Your humor is inadvertent.
{DIALOGUE}: Sensing perhaps Bass's laughter might be at his expense, Epps presses.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Then share what's funny.
{DIALOGUE}: Or what ills you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: I'm here to complete the work at hand.
{DIALOGUE}: As requested, and as paid.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Something rubs you wrongly.
{DIALOGUE}: Before I take further offense, I offer you the opportunity to speak on it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: You ask plainly, I will tell you plainly.
{DIALOGUE}: What I find amusing: You worry about my well being in the heat but, quite frankly, the condition of your laborers--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: "The condition of my..." What in the hell are you--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: It is horrid.
{DIALOGUE}: It's all wrong.
{DIALOGUE}: All wrong, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: They ain't hired help.
{DIALOGUE}: They're my slaves.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: You say that with pride.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: I say it as fact.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: If the conversation concerns what is factual and what is not; there's no justice nor righteousness in slavery.
{DIALOGUE}: I wouldn't own a slave if I was rich as Croesus, which I am not, as is perfectly well understood.
{DIALOGUE}: More particularly among my creditors.
{DIALOGUE}: There's another humbug: the credit system.
{DIALOGUE}: Humbug, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: No credit, no debt.
{DIALOGUE}: Credit leads a man into temptation.
{DIALOGUE}: Cash down is the only thing that will deliver him from
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 104.
{META_DATA}: B155 CONTINUED: (3)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: evil.
{DIALOGUE}: But this question of slavery; what right have you to your niggers when you come down to the point?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: What right?
{DIALOGUE}: I bought 'em.
{DIALOGUE}: I paid for 'em.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: Of course you did.
{DIALOGUE}: The law says you have the right to hold a nigger, but begging the law's pardon...it lies.
{DIALOGUE}: Is everything right because the law allows it?
{DIALOGUE}: Suppose they'd pass a law taking away your liberty and making you a slave?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Ha!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: Suppose.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: That ain't a supposable case.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: Because the law states that your liberties are undeniable?
{DIALOGUE}: Because society deems it so?
{DIALOGUE}: Laws change.
{DIALOGUE}: Social systems crumble.
{DIALOGUE}: Universal truths are constant.
{DIALOGUE}: It is a fact, it is a plain fact that what is true and right is true and right for all.
{DIALOGUE}: White and black alike.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Whoa, whoa, whoa.
{DIALOGUE}: Yah compare me to a nigger, Bass?
{DIALOGUE}: Yah might as well ask what the difference is between a white man and a baboon.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, I seen one of them critters in Orleans that knowed just as much as any nigger I got.
{DIALOGUE}: Yah'd call them fellers citizens, I s'pose?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: Look here; you can't laugh me down in that way.
{DIALOGUE}: These niggers are human beings.
{DIALOGUE}: If they are allowed to scale no higher than brute animals, you and men like you will have to answer for it.
{DIALOGUE}: There's an
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ILL--
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 105.
{META_DATA}: B155 CONTINUED: (4)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Ahhh!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: A fearful ill, resting on this
{META_DATA}: NATION--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: You betray yourself a foreigner!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: That will not go unpunished forever.
{DIALOGUE}: There will be a reckoning yet.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: You like to hear yourself talk, Bass, better than any man I know of.
{DIALOGUE}: Yah'd argue that black was white, or white black if anybody would contradict you.
{DIALOGUE}: A fine supposition if yah lived among Yankees in New England.
{DIALOGUE}: But yah don't.
{META_DATA}: (POINTED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: You most assuredly do not.
{META_DATA}: 155
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's the Sabbath.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The slaves are left to themselves to do their own chores.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At the moment the female slaves are washing their clothes in large cauldrons, slapping their clothes against washing boards and hanging them up to dry near to their living quarters behind the plantation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is a sight of ritual.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Missing from the field of labor is Patsey, for whom Epps hollers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Patsey... Patsey!
{DIALOGUE}: A drunk Epps asks of the slaves:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Where is she?
{DIALOGUE}: Where is Patsey?
{DIALOGUE}: No one answers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Talk, Damn you!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PHEBE
{DIALOGUE}: We know nothin' of her, Massa.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: The hell you don't!
{DIALOGUE}: You know where she is!
{DIALOGUE}: She run off, ain't she?
{DIALOGUE}: She's escaped, and you miserable black dogs stand like
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 106.
{META_DATA}: 155 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: the deef and dumb.
{DIALOGUE}: Speak!
{DIALOGUE}: Speak!
{DIALOGUE}: Not a word spoken.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: My best cotton picking nigger!
{DIALOGUE}: My best.
{DIALOGUE}: A beat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I'd give yah all up for her.
{DIALOGUE}: Where she gone?
{DIALOGUE}: The slaves say nothing.
{DIALOGUE}: There is nothing for them to say.
{DIALOGUE}: They don't know where she is.
{DIALOGUE}: Eventually Epps drops into true sorrow.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: She gone... My Pats gone.
{META_DATA}: 156
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. EPPS'S PLANTATION - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Epps sits on the piazza looking quite forlorn.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks up only to see PATSEY RETURNING TO THE PLANTATION.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Epps steps up to greet her, with anger rather than relief.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they hear his angry voice, the slaves step around from where they are hanging their laundry to dry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Treach is near as well.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Run off.
{DIALOGUE}: Run off, did you?
{META_DATA}: PATSEY
{META_DATA}: MASSA EPPS--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: You miserable wench!
{DIALOGUE}: Where you been?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: I been nowhere.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Lies to your misdeeds!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: The Sabbath day, Massa.
{DIALOGUE}: I took me a walk to commune wit da Lord.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Bring the Lord into yer deceptions?
{DIALOGUE}: Yah Godless... Shaw's.
{DIALOGUE}: Comin' from Shaw's plantation weren't yah?
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 106A.
{META_DATA}: 156 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: ...No...
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 107.
{META_DATA}: 156 CONTINUED: (2)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Yah took yerself ta pleasure Shaw.
{DIALOGUE}: Yah gave baser passion to that unblushin' libertine!
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon tries to intervene:
{META_DATA}: SOLOMON
{META_DATA}: MASTER EPPS--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Now yah speak?
{DIALOGUE}: Now that yah want to add to 'er lies yah find yer tongue.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps goes to strike Solomon, but Patsey pulls his arm back.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: Do not strike him.
{DIALOGUE}: I went to Massa Shaw's plantation!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Yah admit it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: Freely.
{DIALOGUE}: And you know why.
{DIALOGUE}: Patsey takes soap from the pocket of her dress.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I got this from Mistress Shaw.
{DIALOGUE}: Mistress Epps won't even grant me no soap ta clean with.
{DIALOGUE}: Stink so much I make myself gag.
{DIALOGUE}: Five hundred pounds 'a cotton day in, day out.
{DIALOGUE}: More than any man here.
{DIALOGUE}: And 'fo that I will be clean; that all I ax.
{DIALOGUE}: Dis here what I went to Shaw's 'fo.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: You lie...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: The Lord knows that's all.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: You lie!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: And you blind wit yer own covetousness.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't lie, Massa.
{DIALOGUE}: If you kill me, I'll stick ta that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: I'll learn you to go to Shaw's.
{DIALOGUE}: Treach, go get some line.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 108.
{META_DATA}: 156 CONTINUED: (3)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Treach runs quickly to the tool shed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In short order he returns with the rope in hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Strip her.
{DIALOGUE}: Strike her bare 'n lash her to the post.
{DIALOGUE}: Mistress Epps has now come from the Great House.
{DIALOGUE}: She gazes on the scene with an air of heartless satisfaction.
{DIALOGUE}: Now tied to the post, Epps stands behind Patsey with his whip.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Yah done this to yerself, Pats!
{DIALOGUE}: Epps hoists the whip to strike, holds it high...but no matter his rage, Epps cannot bring himself to deliver the blow.
{DIALOGUE}: He looks to Mistress Epps who now stands gloating and spurring him on.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Do it!
{DIALOGUE}: Strike the life from her.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps again hoists the whip.
{DIALOGUE}: It trembles in his hand ahead of the act... But he does not have it in him to deliver such a beating.
{DIALOGUE}: Turning to Solomon, thrusting the whip at him:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Beat her.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon doesn't move.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps shoves the whip into his hand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Give her the whip.
{DIALOGUE}: Give it all to her!
{DIALOGUE}: Patsey, begging to Solomon:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: I'd rather it you, Platt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Strike her, or yah'll get the same!
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 109.
{META_DATA}: 156 CONTINUED: (4)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon takes a step back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He unfurls the whip... He begins to whip Patsey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Lash after lash, Patsey squirms before it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Epps eyes fill with tears, he is nearly too distraught to watch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But the Mistress... She is not satisfied with Solomon's half-hearted effort.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MISTRESS EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: He pantomimes.
{DIALOGUE}: There ain't barely a welt on her.
{DIALOGUE}: That's what your niggers make of yah; a fool fer the takin'.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps's grief is replaced by fury.
{DIALOGUE}: EPPS GRABS THE PISTOL FROM TREACH'S HOLSTER and draws down on the slaves.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Yah will strike her.
{DIALOGUE}: Yah will strike her until her flesh is rent and meat and blood flow equal, or I will kill every nigger in my sight!
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon can't strike a blow, even if it means his life.
{DIALOGUE}: But from the ground, from Patsey:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: Do it, Platt.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't stop until I am dead.
{DIALOGUE}: What else can he do?
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon begins to whip, to truly whip Patsey.
{DIALOGUE}: Her back welts, then tears... Patsey screams in agony.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon strikes again and again... After a full thirty lashes Solomon looks to Epps, who is not satisfied.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Until I say no more!
{DIALOGUE}: I ain't said nothing!
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon strikes another ten to fifteen times.
{DIALOGUE}: By now, as promised, Patsey's back has been reduced to LITTLE MORE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THAN TORN MEAT AND BLOOD.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finally, Solomon holds low the whip.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He can and will do no more.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Strike her!
{DIALOGUE}: Strike her!
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon will not.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps takes up the whip and whips Patsey with "ten fold" greater force than he had.
{DIALOGUE}: The painfully loud and angry curses of Epps load the air.
{DIALOGUE}: Patsey by now is terribly lacerated, literally flayed.
{DIALOGUE}: The lash wet with blood which flowed down her sides and dropped upon the ground.
{DIALOGUE}: At length Patsey ceases struggling.
{DIALOGUE}: Her head sinks listlessly on the ground.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 110.
{META_DATA}: 156 CONTINUED: (5)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Her screams and supplications gradually decrease and die away into a low moan.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It would seem that she was dying.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon, screaming at Epps:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Thou devil!
{DIALOGUE}: Sooner or later, somewhere in the course of eternal justice thou shalt answer for this sin!
{DIALOGUE}: Though Epps fronts rage, there should be underlying anguish for what he has done to his beloved Pats.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: No sin!
{DIALOGUE}: There is no sin!
{DIALOGUE}: A man does how he pleases with his property.
{DIALOGUE}: At the moment, Platt, I am of great pleasure.
{DIALOGUE}: You be goddamn careful I don't come to wantin' to lightenin' my mood no further.
{DIALOGUE}: By contrast to this horror, the field of cotton smiles in the warm sunlight.
{DIALOGUE}: The birds chirp merrily amidst the foliage of the tress.
{DIALOGUE}: Peace and happiness seems to reign everywhere.
{DIALOGUE}: Everywhere else.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps leaves Patsey to herself.
{DIALOGUE}: He says not a word to the Mistress as he passes.
{DIALOGUE}: The Mistress herself heads back into the house.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon unties Patsey, lifts her and takes her to the cabin.
{META_DATA}: 157
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. CABIN - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Patsey is laid on some boards where she remains for a long time with eyes closed and groaning in agony.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Phebe applies melted tallow to her wounds, and all try to assist and console her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In time Patsey opens her eyes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks to Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She does not say a word.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She just looks at him...and then her eyes close again.
{META_DATA}: 158
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MOVED TO A155
{META_DATA}: 159 MOVED TO B155
{META_DATA}: 111.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 160 INT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/GREAT HOUSE/ADDITION -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -APRIL, 1852- Solomon and Bass are working together alone on the extension.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From the amount of work that's been done on it, it should be obvious that days have now passed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon makes a cautious approach to Bass.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As casually as he can he inquires:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Master Bass, I want to ask you what part of the country you came from?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: No part of this land.
{DIALOGUE}: I was born in Canada.
{DIALOGUE}: Now guess where that is.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, I know where Canada is.
{DIALOGUE}: I have been there myself.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: Have you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Montreal and Kingston and Queenston and a great many places.
{DIALOGUE}: And I have been in York state, too.
{DIALOGUE}: Buffalo and Rochester and Albany, and can tell you the names of the villages on the Erie canal and the Champlain canal.
{DIALOGUE}: Bass gives Solomon a long and curious stare.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: Well traveled for a slave.
{DIALOGUE}: How came you here?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Master Bass, if justice had been done I never would have been here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: How's this?
{DIALOGUE}: Tell me all about it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I am afraid to tell you, though I don't believe you would tell Master Epps if I should.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: Every word you speak is a profound secret.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 112-115.
{META_DATA}: 160 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon holds a moment.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hasn't he heard the same promise before?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Prior to Solomon stating his case, WE FADE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 161 INT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION / ADDITION - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hours have passed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bass reflects on the story that Epps has told in the intervening.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: How many years all told?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Just nearly...just passed eleven.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: Your story is...it is amazing, and in no good way.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Do you believe, sir, in justice as you have said?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: I do.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: That slavery is an evil that should befall none?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: I believe so.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: If you truly do, I would ask...I would beg that you write my friends in the north, acquainting them with my situation and beseeching them to forward free papers, or take such steps as they might consider proper to secure my release.
{DIALOGUE}: Bass looks at Solomon, holding his gaze for more than a prolonged beat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: My daughter Margaret is possibly now 19 and my son Alonzo, 16.
{DIALOGUE}: I miss them so.
{DIALOGUE}: It would be an unspeakable happiness to clasp my wife and my family again.
{DIALOGUE}: Bass hands Solomon an end of a long plank of wood and looks over his shoulder, as if to camouflage the conversation by work.
{DIALOGUE}: They both lift it toward the floorboards.
{DIALOGUE}: Finally Bass speaks.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 116.
{META_DATA}: 161 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: I have always forgone relationships and family.
{DIALOGUE}: I did once have a sweetheart who I loved deeply.
{DIALOGUE}: Bass points to a measuring tool, which Solomon immediately hands over.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: But that was a long, long time ago.
{DIALOGUE}: I've been traveling this country for the best part of twenty years.
{DIALOGUE}: My freedom is everything.
{DIALOGUE}: The fact that I can walk out of here tomorrow gives me most pleasure.
{DIALOGUE}: I see the aching in your eyes, the pain of not being attached to your loved ones.
{DIALOGUE}: My life doesn't mean much to anyone, but it seems your life means a lot to a lot of people.
{DIALOGUE}: What you have just said to me scares me, and I must say, sir, I am afraid.
{DIALOGUE}: Not just for you, but for me.
{DIALOGUE}: They continue working, fixing the floorboards in unison.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon, slightly confused.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I will write your letter sir, for if I could bring freedom to you, it will be more than a pleasure.
{DIALOGUE}: It will be a duty.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, would you be so kind as to pass me those nails, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: We pull back to reveal the two men dwarfed by the unfinished structure.
{DIALOGUE}: They continue to work, as if the conversation had never occurred.
{META_DATA}: 162
{META_DATA}: OMIT
{META_DATA}: 163 OMIT
{META_DATA}: 164 OMIT
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: A165 EXT. SWAMP TBD
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon walks a path he has walked a thousand times or more on his way back from Bartholomew's - sack familiarly slung over his right shoulder.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Drearily he walks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His eyes acknowledge something we yet cannot see to his left.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Almost simultaneously, his eyes retract back to the path
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 116A.
{META_DATA}: A165 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: towards Epps'.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he passes out of shot, the evidence of what he was looking at is revealed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FEET hang at the top right hand corner of the frame.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A woman, who has been lynched.
{META_DATA}: 165
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/ADDITION - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -SEPTEMBER, 1852-
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SLOW DISSOLVE
{DIALOGUE}: To a now virtually complete, half-painted white gazebo.
{DIALOGUE}: Slaves continue to work on it.
{DIALOGUE}: As they do so, Bass peels away from the structure to have an overview.
{DIALOGUE}: He beckons Solomon toward him, out of earshot from the slaves who are continuing to work on the gazebo.
{DIALOGUE}: As Solomon approaches, Bass shouts-
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: And bring those markers!
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon gathers a clutch of markers in his hands and approaches Bass.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: No letter yet.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: You are certain?
{DIALOGUE}: Bass takes a marker from Solomon and slides it into the earth.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: I have inquired thoroughly.
{DIALOGUE}: More than is safe for either of us.
{DIALOGUE}: Bass takes another and pokes it into the ground, improvising a pathway towards the gazebo.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon...I have a job or two on hand which will be completed shortly... The work here has grown sparse.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 117.
{META_DATA}: 165 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bass doesn't need to spell things out for Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon's understanding of the finality of the situation should be very clear.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: You must know, wherever I am I will press your cause.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Five months.
{DIALOGUE}: On top of these years.
{DIALOGUE}: No cause remains.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: If there is any chance...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Bass...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BASS
{DIALOGUE}: I will continue to write your
{META_DATA}: PEOPLE--
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Go home knowing you have tried.
{DIALOGUE}: The weight of defeat should hang very heavily with both men.
{DIALOGUE}: Nothing more to do, nothing more to say BASS TAKES
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SOLOMON'S HAND, GRIPS IT FIRMLY, BUT LOW AND SURREPTITIOUSLY knowing full well he cannot be seen making contact with a slave.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But in the strength of their collective grip, in the emotion in which they hold each other's eyes, we should be able to easily see how greatly Bass wanted to be able to help Solomon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Equally, we can see the depth of regard Solomon has for Bass.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The moment is made all the more powerful by the fact neither man can openly speak his regret or thanks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A moment longer, and then Bass releases his grip and makes his way marching toward the gazebo, pointing instructions.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon is left, markers in hand, alone.
{META_DATA}: 166
{META_DATA}: OMIT
{META_DATA}: 167 OMIT
{META_DATA}: 118.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: A168 EXT. ROAD BY EPPS' PLANTATION - EVENING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon sits on a secluded part of the road, fiddle in hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He stares across the expanse.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His eyes fixed on something that is a million miles away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Slowly Solomon tunes his fiddle, turning the tuning peg tighter and tighter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the strings are taut, the sound is almost unbearable as Solomon tightens bit by bit, as if bones are being cracked one by one.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Just beyond the breaking point of sound, there is a snap.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He then repeats the action.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon holds the neck of the violin.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sliding his thumb and forefinger down the neck, he methodically cracks it at the base.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He carefully snaps the neck and removes it from the body, then snaps it in two, placing it on the ground.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He then starts on the body.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Heaving it on the ground, it falls apart.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Methodically he breaks the violin into small bits - silencing the instrument with a hushed display of violence, rather than aggressive.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Seems almost to be, in an odd way, respectful.
{META_DATA}: 168
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MASTER EPPS'S PLANTATION/FIELD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -FEBRUARY, 1853- The Slaves are sewing the heavily plowed field, making their way in the trying soil.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon, too focused to note the arrival of two men by carriage: Parker and the
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SHERIFF.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: While the Sheriff makes his way to the field, Parker remains with the carriage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Sheriff calls:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHERIFF
{DIALOGUE}: Platt...?
{DIALOGUE}: Where is the boy called Platt?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: ...Sir... The Sheriff crosses to him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHERIFF
{DIALOGUE}: Your name is Platt, is it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: Pointing off to the distance.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHERIFF
{DIALOGUE}: Do you know that man?
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 118A.
{META_DATA}: 168 CONTINUED:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon looks toward the carriage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He has to shield his eyes from the sun.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Recognition is slow coming to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But when it does, it hits him as a rush.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Parker...?
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 119.
{META_DATA}: 168 CONTINUED: (2)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon starts for Parker, but he is pulled back by the Sheriff who is keen to determine Solomon's true identity.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHERIFF
{DIALOGUE}: Say again?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Parker?
{DIALOGUE}: As he does, Epps makes his way over.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHERIFF
{DIALOGUE}: That man received a letter compiling many accusations.
{DIALOGUE}: You look me in the eye and on your life answer me truthfully: have you any other name than Platt?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon Northup is my name.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Sheriff...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHERIFF
{DIALOGUE}: Have you a family?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: What's all this?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHERIFF
{DIALOGUE}: It's official business.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: My nigger, my business.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHERIFF
{DIALOGUE}: Your business waits.
{META_DATA}: (TO SOLOMON)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tell me of your family.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I have a wife and two children.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHERIFF
{DIALOGUE}: What were your children's names?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Margaret and Alonzo.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHERIFF
{DIALOGUE}: And your wife's name before her marriage?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Anne Hampton.
{DIALOGUE}: I am who I say.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon pushes past the sheriff.
{DIALOGUE}: As Solomon moves toward Parker, his pace quickens with each step until his
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 119A.
{META_DATA}: 168 CONTINUED: (3)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: personal velocity has him nearly at a dead run.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The two old friends make contact with each other, wrap each other in a long and emotional embrace.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It if finally broken by Epps, who has moved over with the Sheriff.
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 120.
{META_DATA}: 168 CONTINUED: (4)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: Nah... You will unhand 'em.
{DIALOGUE}: Platt is my nigger!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PARKER
{DIALOGUE}: He is Solomon Northup.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: You say...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PARKER
{DIALOGUE}: He belongs to no man.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: You say!
{DIALOGUE}: You come here, unfamiliar to me, and make claims.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHERIFF
{DIALOGUE}: Not claims.
{DIALOGUE}: I have no doubts.
{DIALOGUE}: This is Solomon Northup, a resident of Saratoga Springs, NY.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: To hell with that!
{DIALOGUE}: My nigger, and I'll fight you for 'em!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PARKER
{DIALOGUE}: As is your right.
{DIALOGUE}: As it will be my pleasure to bankrupt you in the courts.
{DIALOGUE}: Your decision.
{DIALOGUE}: By this time, the slaves in the plantation have overcome their fear of penalty, and left their work and gathered in the yard as witnesses.
{DIALOGUE}: They stand behind the cabin, out of sight of Epps.
{DIALOGUE}: Mistress Epps also bears witness, standing on the veranda next to her house slave.
{DIALOGUE}: Her face is of a strange mixed emotion.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps looks to Solomon.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon icily, stoically holds his ground.
{DIALOGUE}: He makes it quite clear in his countenance that nobody owns him.
{DIALOGUE}: Sheriff, hand on his gun, is there to back Solomon up.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps, with no other recourse than to
{META_DATA}: BACK DOWN:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS
{DIALOGUE}: You think this is the last you'll see of me, boy?
{DIALOGUE}: It ain't.
{META_DATA}: (TO PARKER)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Whatever paper you hold about his freedom, it don't mean naught.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is my nigger - and I will have my day in court, sir.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As God as my witness, I will have my day in court.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Take 'em!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Epps calls to Bob-
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 120A.
{META_DATA}: 168 CONTINUED: (5)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: EPPS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Saddle my horse!
{DIALOGUE}: And bring her up here.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps walks back into the plantation.
{DIALOGUE}: The trio starts for the carriage.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon is pulled back by the call of Patsey's voice:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PATSEY
{DIALOGUE}: Platt... Disregarding Parker, Solomon crosses over to Patsey.
{DIALOGUE}: Under the circumstances, neither really knows how to engage.
{DIALOGUE}: Finally, suddenly, Patsey throws her arms around Solomon and they embrace.
{DIALOGUE}: Epps, now mounted on his horse, witness the encounter.
{DIALOGUE}: Kicking the stirrups hard into the sides of the horse, he rides off furiously.
{DIALOGUE}: Calling from the carriage, mindful of Epps:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PARKER
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon...if we know what's wise, we should depart.
{DIALOGUE}: A moment longer Solomon and Patsey hold each other.
{DIALOGUE}: They separate, Solomon heading back to the carriage.
{DIALOGUE}: He and Parker alight.
{DIALOGUE}: The Sheriff chides the horses and they
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 121.
{META_DATA}: 168 CONTINUED: (6)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: start up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they move on, Patsey sinks down to the ground, where she remains in a weary and half-reclining state, the other slaves around her.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WE STAY WITH Solomon as he travels further and further from the slaves - who are diminished by distance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon waves a hand to them, but the carriage rounds a bend and a thicket of trees hides them from his eyes forever more.
{META_DATA}: BLACK
{META_DATA}: A169
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. NORTHUP HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -MARCH, 1853- We now see Solomon in front of a door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A door we have seen before at the very beginning of our story.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon, aged significantly since then, stands nervously, swallowing, and adjusting his attire.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He breaths in and holds his breath.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He blows out and closes his eyes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A tear falls from his cheek, but this is not the way he wants his family to see him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He gathers himself, and looks to his right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There stands Mr. Parker.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He places his hand on Solomon's shoulder.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He says gently-
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PARKER
{DIALOGUE}: Are you ready?
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon swallows and nods.
{META_DATA}: 169
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. NORTHUP HOUSE - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE DOOR TO THE ROOM OPENS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mr. Parker enters, Solomon behind.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We first see Anne, in her finest attire; the Northup children: Alonzo, who is now seventeen and Margaret who is now twenty - SHE CARRIES WITH HER A BUNDLE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Also present is MARGARET'S HUSBAND.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The family waits patiently, dutifully...but anxiously.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Anne rises to greet him, but holds back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: All around, the body language of the family is stiff and awkward.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are, after all - after twelve years - little more than familiar strangers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: I apologize for my appearance.
{DIALOGUE}: I have had a difficult time of things these past many years.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon looks among his family; trying to recall them as much as they look to see familiarity within him.
{DIALOGUE}: To his
{META_DATA}: CHILDREN:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Alonzo... Margaret, yes?
{DIALOGUE}: You do not recognize me, do you?
{DIALOGUE}: Do
{META_DATA}: (MORE) (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 122.
{META_DATA}: 169 CONTINUED:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: you...do you even remember the last time we saw each other?
{DIALOGUE}: I put you on a carriage with your mother... Margaret, tearing, hugs her father.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon almost breaks, but he keeps himself together.
{DIALOGUE}: Looking to the
{META_DATA}: UNKNOWN MAN:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: And who is this?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARGARET
{DIALOGUE}: He is my husband.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: Husband?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARGARET'S HUSBAND
{DIALOGUE}: It is very good to meet you, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: We have much acquainting to do.
{DIALOGUE}: Margaret rises, she presents her bundle to her father.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MARGARET
{DIALOGUE}: And this is your grandson.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon Northup Staunton.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON
{DIALOGUE}: ...Solomon... The fact his grandson carries his name, is overwhelming.
{DIALOGUE}: Solomon breaks down.
{DIALOGUE}: Emotionally, physically... But ANNE IS THERE TO CATCH HIM.
{DIALOGUE}: As she holds him, Solomon says to Anne with all his heart:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOLOMON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Forgive me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANNE
{DIALOGUE}: There is nothing to forgive.
{DIALOGUE}: The pair, joined now by the whole family, hold on to each other for life...and one would think for all the rest of their lives.
{META_DATA}: FADE TO:
{META_DATA}: BLACK
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARD:
{DIALOGUE}: Upon gaining his freedom, Solomon Northup located and attempted to seek legal justice against the men who kidnapped him.
{DIALOGUE}: The case was tried in Washington, DC where blacks were prohibited by law from testifying
{META_DATA}: (CONTINUED)
{META_DATA}: 123.
{META_DATA}: 169 CONTINUED: (2)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: against whites.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The charges against the kidnappers were eventually dismissed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Northup spent the rest of his life working as an abolitionist, and with the Underground Railroad.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Solomon Northup most likely died between 1863 and 1875.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The exact date, place, and circumstances of his death remain unknown.
{META_DATA}: - END -
